10</strong> <a class="get-post" href="#" data-id="56" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal">5 Simple Ways To Improve Virtual Meetings</a> <strong>May 15, 2010</strong> <a class="get-post" href="#" data-id="55" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal">Active Listening Goes - Up In The Air</a> <strong>May 15, 2010</strong></div>', '1', 'en'),
(22, '2016-12-17 12:52:39', '2016-12-17 12:54:12', 1, 'events', 'Subscribe to the Red Carpet', '', '<div id="email-subscribe">\r\n<p>We hope you enjoyed the Red Carpet, to receive it directly in your email inbox, enter your email below. We promise not to spam you every hour with senseless junkmail!</p>\r\n<form style="margin-bottom: 3;" action="//visitor.constantcontact.com/d.jsp" method="post" name="ccoptin" target="_blank">\r\n<h2 class="text-center">Sign up to Receive Red Carpet - Our Email newsletter</h2>\r\n<input name="ea" type="text" /><input name="go" type="submit" value="SUBMIT" /> <input name="m" type="hidden" value="1101971666321" /> <input name="p" type="hidden" value="oi" /></form></div>', '1', 'en'),
(23, '2016-12-17 13:03:20', '2016-12-17 13:03:20', 1, 'contact', 'Contact Us', '', '<h3>Worldwide Headquarters</h3>\r\n<p>516 N. Ogden Ave. Suite 221<br /> Chicago, IL 60642<br /> USA<br /> 773-572-8616</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Regional Phone Numbers:</p>\r\n<p><strong>United States:</strong> 888-393-4730</p>\r\n<p><strong>India:</strong> +919 890 013421</p>\r\n<p><strong>London:</strong> +44 7791 809 421</p>\r\n<p><strong>Dubai:</strong> +00971 555 328 525</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>Facebook</strong></span><br /> <a href="http://www.facebook.com/PinnaclePerformance" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"> PinnaclePerformance @ Facebook</a></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>Twitter</strong></span><br /> <a href="http://www.twitter.com/Pinnacletweets" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pinnacletweets</a></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>LinkedIn</strong></span><br /> <a href="http://www.linkedin.com/company/pinnacle-performance-company" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Pinnacle Perfomance Company</a></p>', '1', 'en'),
(24, '2016-12-18 11:16:34', '2016-12-18 11:34:35', 1, 'company', 'Customized Training Programs', '', '<h3>Nothing is "off-the-shelf"</h3>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance (!) does not deliver anything stock. Every workshop is customized and uniquely designed following our three-stage process. Our Core Building Blocks teach you how to incorporate the Pinnacle Method in your communication, and our Auxiliary Building Blocks are custom modules that help you apply our methodology to your specific circumstances.</p>\r\n<table style="height: 200px; width: 1196px;" border="0" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="1">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>core building blocks\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>- First Impressions</li>\r\n<li>- Snapshot Profile</li>\r\n<li>- Overcoming Stage Fright</li>\r\n<li>- Projecting a Confident Presence</li>\r\n<li>- Vocal Dynamics</li>\r\n<li>- Gestures and Movement</li>\r\n<li>- Intention and Objective</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p><a href="assets/dist/cms/pdf/Building_Blocks.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><img style="border-style: solid; border-width: 0px; height: 150px; margin-left: 10px; margin-right: 10px; width: 116px;" src="assets/dist/cms/img/Building_Blocks.jpg" alt="" /></a></p>\r\n<p><a href="assets/dist/cms/pdf/Building_Blocks.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Download PDF</a></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>auxiliary building blocks</p>\r\n<table style="width: 100%;" border="0" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="1" align="center">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style="vertical-align: top;">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>- Active Listening</li>\r\n<li>- Effective Storytelling</li>\r\n<li>- Reactive Communication</li>\r\n<li>- Presenting to Senior Leadership</li>\r\n<li>- Delivering Difficult News</li>\r\n<li>- Handling Tough Questions</li>\r\n<li>- Stakeholder Analysis</li>\r\n<li>- Master Introductions</li>\r\n<li>- Courtesy Under Fire</li>\r\n<li>- Leading a Team Through Change</li>\r\n<li>- Providing Feedback</li>\r\n<li>- Social Communication</li>\r\n<li>- Customer Service Communication</li>\r\n<li>- Being Assertive</li>\r\n<li>- Running Effective Meetings</li>\r\n<li>- Crafting Your Presentations</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style="vertical-align: top;">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>- One-on-One Communication</li>\r\n<li>- Building Business Relationships</li>\r\n<li>- Media Training</li>\r\n<li>- Managing Conflict</li>\r\n<li>- Utilizing Visual Aids</li>\r\n<li>- Virtual Communication</li>\r\n<li>- Negotiating Basics</li>\r\n<li>- Gaining Stakeholder Commitment</li>\r\n<li>- Positioning Statement/Elevator Pitch</li>\r\n<li>- Memorization Techniques</li>\r\n<li>- Impromptu Speaking</li>\r\n<li>- Simulated Communication/Presentations</li>\r\n<li>- Controlling a Challenging Audience</li>\r\n<li>- Master Interviewing</li>\r\n<li>- Customized (client centric)</li>\r\n<li>- Private Coaching</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', '1', 'en'),
(25, '2016-12-18 11:20:25', '2016-12-19 12:14:51', 1, 'company', 'Leadership', '', '<div id="profiles">\r\n<div class="thumbs">\r\n<div class="imgs" data-bio="3" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal"><img src="../../assets/dist/cms/img/team/1.jpg?resize=e[true]h[120]w[100]" /></div>\r\n<strong>David Lewis</strong>Co-Founder and CEO</div>\r\n<div class="thumbs">\r\n<div class="imgs" data-bio="17" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal"><img src="../../assets/dist/cms/img/team/2.jpg?resize=e[true]h[120]w[100]" /></div>\r\n<strong>G. Riley Mills</strong>Co-Founder and COO</div>\r\n<div class="thumbs">\r\n<div class="imgs" data-bio="4" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal"><img src="../../assets/dist/cms/img/team/3.jpg?resize=e[true]h[120]w[100]" /></div>\r\n<strong>Gerri Leon</strong>VP of Marketing</div>\r\n<div class="thumbs">\r\n<div class="imgs" data-bio="25" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal"><img src="../../assets/dist/cms/img/team/4.jpg?resize=e[true]h[120]w[100]" /></div>\r\n<strong>Brian McNeany</strong>VP of Sales</div>\r\n<div class="thumbs">\r\n<div class="imgs" data-bio="24" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal"><img src="../../assets/dist/cms/img/team/5.jpg?resize=e[true]h[120]w[100]" /></div>\r\n<strong>Tim Kasper</strong>VP for Southeast US Region</div>\r\n<div class="thumbs">\r\n<div class="imgs" data-bio="134" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal"><img src="../../assets/dist/cms/img/team/6.jpg?resize=e[true]h[120]w[100]" /></div>\r\n<strong>Cindy Tegtmeyer</strong>Director Global Executive Accounts</div>\r\n<div class="thumbs">\r\n<div class="imgs" data-bio="279" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal"><img src="../../assets/dist/cms/img/team/7.jpg?resize=e[true]h[120]w[100]" /></div>\r\n<strong>Rob Lynch</strong>Public Relations Director</div>\r\n<div class="thumbs">\r\n<div class="imgs" data-bio="143" data-toggle="modal" data-target="#myModal"><img src="../../assets/dist/cms/img/team/8.jpg?resize=e[true]h[120]w[100]" /></div>\r\n<strong>Brad Lawrence</strong>Editorial Director</div>\r\n</div>', '1', 'en'),
(26, '2016-12-18 11:22:02', '2016-12-18 12:04:27', 1, 'company', 'Global Strategic Partners', '', '<p><img style="float: right;" src="assets/dist/cms/img/innovate.png" alt="Innovative Human Resource Solutions (IHS) Logo" /></p>\r\n<h3>Innovative Human Resource Solutions (IHS)</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Innovative Human Resource Solutions (IHS) will provide Performance-Based communication skills training for Middle East based clients.</strong></p>\r\n<p>Innovative HR Solutions (IHS) specializes in talent identification and development strategies such as assessment &amp; development centres, psychometric assessment and executive coaching. They are also passionate about supporting individuals to develop more effective behaviours that drive greater success for them in the workplace. IHS develop HR strategies to drive the retention and development of talent. They are also licenced to conduct a suite of psychometric accreditation for HR professionals. Recently awarded a Top 100 SME award, IHS can be found at www.ihsdubai.com.</p>\r\n<p>IHS has more than 12 years experience helping some of the world&rsquo;s best employers select, develop, grow and retain talent as well as transform teams and build human resource processes in the Middle East region. The company has a skilled team of organizational psychologists that deliver a range of tailor made business performance solutions.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Innovative HR Solutions (IHS)</strong><br /> Contact: Karen Beggs <a href="mailto:kbeggs@ihsdubai.com">kbeggs@ihsdubai.com</a><br /> Innovative Human Resource Solutions<br /> +971 4 446 1505<br /> <a href="http://www.ihsdubai.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">www.ihsdubai.com</a></p>\r\n<p><img style="float: right;" src="assets/dist/cms/img/arctic-solutions-logo-blue.png" alt="Arctic Solutions Logo" /></p>\r\n<h3>Arctic Solutions</h3>\r\n<p>Arab Center for Training, Improvement and Consultation (ARCTIC Solutions) is successfully providing its clients with business and professional solutions, as well as expertise in the development of human resources.</p>\r\n<p>ARCTIC&rsquo;s founder has more than 40 years of experience in the fields of human resources development and people management.</p>\r\n<p>Today, ARCTIC has Resources available for its training projects include a solid network of Subject Matter Experts (SME&rsquo;s) who combine academic vigour and rigorous operational backgrounds, in addition to instructional teams having the ability to adapt to different types of cultural environments and can effectively transfer know-how across borders with ease.</p>\r\n<p>Instructors in ARCTIC can also present customized, client directed courses in the areas of interest for clients&rsquo; choice. All custom designed courses, or events (hands-on and OJT Plans) can be expanded or condensed to fit the time available for implementing desired training, so that ARCTIC can offer a comprehensive range of training bilingual programs to a large number of private and public organizations.</p>\r\n<p>Continuing with ARCTIC&rsquo;s passion for custom designed courses, it has partnered with Pinnacle Performance Company, which will provide all of ARCTIC&rsquo;s communication and presentation skills training needs.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Arctic Solutions</strong><br /> Jumeirah Lake Towers, Dubai, UAE<br /> Contact: Hazem Zamel<br /> Executive Director<br /> <a href="mailto:hazem.zamel@arctic-solutions.org">hazem.zamel@arctic-solutions.org</a><br /> +971 56 781 8934<br /> +201 000 949 011<br /> <a href="mailto:info@arctic-sloutions.org">info@arctic-sloutions.org</a><br /> <a href="http://www.arctic-solutions.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">www.arctic-solutions.org</a></p>', '1', 'en'),
(27, '2016-12-18 11:23:14', '2016-12-18 12:05:46', 1, 'company', 'Awards', '', '<div class="grouper">\r\n<p><img style="float: left; margin: 0 15px 25px 0; width: 200px;" src="assets/dist/cms/img/award.png" />Pinnacle Performance Company Wins 2015 World Human Resources Development Congress&rsquo; Training Provider Of The Year Award</p>\r\n<p><em>Global Communication Skills Training Firm Wins Four World Human Resources Development Congress Awards, Eight Awards in Last Five Years</em></p>\r\n<p>March 4, 2015, CHICAGO &ndash; Pinnacle Performance Company won four World Human Resources Development (HRD) Congress Awards for 2015, including Training Provider of the Year, Best Service Provider in HR, Innovation in Learning Services for Training and Best Use of Technology For Training for its Virtual Coach.</p>\r\n<p>The global communication skills training firm, which teaches The Pinnacle Method &ndash; the award-winning three step process that applies acting techniques to improve the effectiveness of business communication &ndash;has won eight World Human Resources Development Congress Awards over the last five years. This year&rsquo;s awards join the 2013 Award for Innovation and Learning, the 2012 awards for Best Training Provider and Innovation in Learning and the award for Vendor Innovation in Learning and Training Management in 2011.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;In today&rsquo;s global business environment, cross-cultural communication is critical because even simple communication breakdowns during strategic discussions or presentations can erode credibility and trust,&rdquo; said David Lewis, co-founder and CEO of Pinnacle Performance Company. &rdquo;We&rsquo;re thrilled to receive the World HRD Congress&rsquo; Training Provider of the Year Award, especially as more companies invest in their employee&rsquo;s skillsets and engage communication skills training experts like Pinnacle to help improve their employee\'s presentation and communication skills.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The 23rd annual awards event focused on &ldquo;Mining Human Potential for creating Great Organizations.&rdquo; The awards recognize human resources development professionals and trainers for their achievements. They were also designed to help improve the quality of training and development by sharing best practices and experiences, to continue improving how training and development meets business needs, and to establish direction and contribute to business or organizational success by improving employee performance.</p>\r\n<p>The Human Resources Development Management Committee of the World HRD Congress organizes the awards. The award honors individuals, teams and organizations from the corporate, education, public and private sector that leverage learning and development to significantly advance workforce productivity and performance. The ceremony was held on February 15-17 in Taj Lands End, Mumbai.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img style="float: left; margin: 0 15px 25px 0; width: 200px;" src="assets/dist/cms/img/apac.gif" />Asia Pacific HRM Congress Awards Pinnacle Performance Company 2013 Best Service Provider In Human Resources</p>\r\n<p><em>Award marks the fifth award in three years for the global communication training firm</em></p>\r\n<p>September 26, 2013, CHICAGO &ndash; Pinnacle Performance Company added the Asia Pacific HRM Congress2013 Award for Best Service Provider in Human Resources to its collection. The award is the fifth award in the last three years for the global communication skills training firm that applies acting technique to help business professionals&rsquo; improve their communication skills.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Prior to launching Pinnacle, I hired numerous training vendors and personally experienced countless trainings. We knew that our communication training had to be engaging, customized, immediately applicable and ultimately fun so participants would feel like their time was worth the investment.&rdquo; said David Lewis, CEO and co-founder of Pinnacle Performance Company. &ldquo;We appreciate the recognition, particularly because we have experienced tremendous growth in Asia Pacific over the past two years.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>The Best Service Provider in Human Resources Awardis organized by the Human Resources Management Committee of the Asia Pacific HRM Congress. The award honors individuals, teams and organizations from the corporate, education, public and private sector who use learning and development to significantly advance workforce productivity and performance. The award ceremony was held on September 6, 2013, in Bangalore, India.</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance also has received four HRD World Congress Awards:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>2013 award for Innovation in Learning</li>\r\n<li>2012 awards for Best Training Provider and Innovation in Learning</li>\r\n<li>2011 award for Vendor Innovation in Learning and Training Management</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Several global companies trust Pinnacle Performance Company to help their emerging leaders, front line staff and senior executives improve, sharpen and hone their business communication skills.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</div>', '1', 'en'),
(28, '2016-12-19 06:27:33', '2016-12-19 06:47:38', 1, 'events-tab', 'Pinnacle Performance Company Now Trains In Nearly 40 Countries', 'Pinnacle in the News', '<p><em>Global communication skills training firm adds South America to training footprint and multilingual training in Spanish and Portuguese</em></p>\r\n<p>September 25, 2014, CHICAGO &ndash; Pinnacle Performance Company, a global communication skills training firm, now trains in nearly 40 countries. The company, which teaches business professionals at Fortune 1000 companies how to influence audiences using Intention-based communication, added South America to its growing training footprint by conducting experiential workshops in Spanish and Portuguese for a global mobile device maker&rsquo;s S&atilde;o Paulo, Brazil, office.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;We have seen steady growth throughout the UK, India and China and we&rsquo;re excited to add South America to the growing number of countries where we have trained while adding multilingual training to our evolving capabilities,&rdquo; said David Lewis, co-founder and CEO of Pinnacle Performance Company. &ldquo;Through our unique three step process, we teach business professionals around the world how to engage and influence in social settings, work meetings, conference calls, presentations or any other essential communication.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company has offices in Chicago, London, Bangalore and Dubai.</p>\r\n<p><strong>About Pinnacle Performance Company</strong><br /> Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp;provides individuals, from introverts to polished speakers, with the tools and techniques needed to become more influential communicators. By applying our innovative, three-step process, we show you how focusing on your message\'s objective and delivery will allow you to achieve specific audience reactions, captivate your audience and communicate like a true leader. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&rsquo;s exclusive Master Trainers have trained thousands of business people worldwide, including CEOs, senior executives, professional speakers, sales people, trainers, engineers, customer service reps and more. Its client roster includes well-recognized brands and blue chip companies like Allstate, Capgemini, Qualcomm, Walgreens, RR Donnelley, Oracle, Barclays, Underwriters Laboratories, Apple, IBM, Devon Energy, Spectra Energy, CITGO, Shell, Wells Fargo, KPMG, Emirates Airlines, Infosys and more.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(29, '2016-12-19 06:44:26', '2016-12-19 06:47:24', 1, 'events-tab', 'Gulf War Veteran Benjamin Host Shares His Story With Pepperdine Choral Students To Inspire April 13th Tribute & Benefit Performance', 'Pinnacle in the News', '<div><em>Host shaped and delivered his 60-minute speech using communication skills learned in Pinnacle Performance Company workshop</em></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><em>Host shares experiences to educate on veterans&rsquo; post trauma needs and inspire those returning from war</em></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>CHICAGO (March 01, 2013)</strong> &ndash; For Benjamin Host, every day is a blessing. The retired Navy Petty Officer suffered a severe traumatic brain injury in a Humvee convoy accident in 2004. Host was a member of the Seebees, the United States Navy construction battalion, which builds and maintains remote bases to support troop activities.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Host was transported to a field hospital where two holes were drilled into his skull to relieve the swelling and immediately airlifted to Baghdad for emergency brain surgery. He had three brain surgeries, has a plate in his head held in with multiple screws and an open area not covered by skull.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Like many soldiers, he suffered from post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), survivor&rsquo;s guilt and challenges adjusting to civilian life after returning to the states. Determined to not let PTSD take over his life, Host posits, &ldquo;Who you are now, is now who you used to be. You have an opportunity to grow into who you&rsquo;re going to become.&rdquo;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Living that mantra, Host says he turned his limp into a strut and is determined to help other returning soldiers. By sharing his experiences with wider audiences, he intends for other soldiers to learn they&rsquo;re not alone and to advance ways to help soldiers adjust to a different life.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>On September 13 of last year, Host spoke on a panel entitled "Transitions &amp; New Beginnings - Linking Alliances to Evolving Needs" at the 2012 Warrior-Family Symposium, cosponsored by Military Officers Association of America (MOAA) and the National Defense Industrial Association, in Washington, D.C. His and another soldier&rsquo;s testimony were given to address the &ldquo;growing and changing needs of the wounded warrior population, and provided helpful feedback to the organizations and government programs that assist them.&rdquo;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>He also recently shared his experience with Pepperdine&rsquo;s choir students, San Diego State University&rsquo;s Chamber Singers, and the Malibu High School&rsquo;s Chamber Choir to help inspire their upcoming tribute and benefit concert on April 13th.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>To prepare for the Pepperdine speech, Host worked with G. Riley Mills, Pinnacle Performance Company&rsquo;s co-founder and chief operating officer, to develop the core theme and supporting messages as well as the presentation&rsquo;s structure, build, and flow to effectively keep the audience engaged. Mills also coached Host on how to anticipate and properly prepare for difficult questions during the Q&amp;A session at the end. Before the Pepperdine speech, Host attended a two-day Pinnacle Performance Company communication and presentation skills workshop organized by his employer that focused on how he delivered his messages.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&ldquo;Ben is a good kid with an amazing story to tell,&rdquo; said Mills. &ldquo;He has all the content, it was just a matter of helping him shape it.&rdquo;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Host said, &ldquo;My heart&rsquo;s desire is to be a light for all groups affected by the struggles many face in the transitioning from war time experiences. Gary has been nothing short of a blessing to me in the contributions he has made to my life. He has helped me to be more than just a voice that speaks to people, but rather has showed me good strategies to getting my voice to where it needs to be to help make a lasting impact for organizations like the Wounded Warriors, and with those who want to learn about the lasting effects of war on soldiers today.&rdquo;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>About Pinnacle Performance Company</strong></div>\r\n<div>Pinnacle Performance Company provides individuals, from introverts to polished speakers, with the tools and techniques needed to become more influential communicators. By applying our innovative, three-step process, we show you how focusing on your message\'s objective and delivery will allow you to achieve specific audience reactions, captivate your audience and communicate like a true leader. &nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Pinnacle Performance Company&rsquo;s exclusive master instructors have trained thousands of business people worldwide, including CEOs, senior executives, professional speakers, sales people, trainers, engineers, customer service reps and more. Its client roster includes well recognized brands and blue chip companies like Allstate, Capgemini, Qualcomm, Walgreens, RR Donnelley, Oracle, Barclays, Underwriters Laboratories, Apple, IBM, Devon Energy, Spectra Energy, CITGO, Shell, Wells Fargo, KPMG, Emirates Airlines, Infosys and more.</div>', '1', 'en'),
(30, '2016-12-19 06:47:01', '2016-12-19 06:47:01', 1, 'events-tab', 'Pinnacle Performance Company’s Virtual Coach Provides Affordable, Convenient And Scalable Presentation And Communication Skills Training', 'Pinnacle in the News', '<div><em>Complements learning and development and field sales training programs by assessing and developing large groups of disparate employees&nbsp;</em></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>CHICAGO (December 10, 2012)</strong> &ndash; Pinnacle Performance Company&rsquo;s Virtual Coach provides affordable, convenient and scalable communication and presentation skills training. It helps learning and development and field sales training managers identify emerging leaders, sales superstars and burgeoning executives and assess and develop their communication skills accordingly.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div align="center"><img style="width: 288px; height: 196px;" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/VcoachComputer.png" alt="" /></div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&ldquo;Global businesses face several unique training and development challenges, including reducing costs, cultural differences, time and opportunity costs and geographic differences,&rdquo; said Dave Lewis, co-founder and CEO of Pinnacle Performance Company. &ldquo;With Virtual Coach, we can cost effectively evaluate a business professional&rsquo;s communication skills whenever they&rsquo;re available and wherever they are and provide the same customized, individualized feedback and exercises for improvement we would in an in- person workshop.&rdquo;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>Using Virtual Coach is simple:</strong></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Create an account at http://www.pinper.com/vcoach.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Each individual shoots approximately five minutes of video on a camera, webcam or smartphone and uploads it to Pinnacle&rsquo;s secure and private portal.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>A certified Pinnacle Performance master trainer views the video and evaluates how the individual communicates, their presence and ability to engage and influence. They provide a comprehensive, customized performance report highlighting strengths and areas for improvement and offer specific exercises to strengthen communication. Both individuals and managers can receive the reports. Pinnacle&rsquo;s master instructors also are available for virtual coaching via phone or web conference.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>Individual performance reports are $250 a piece. Virtual coaching with a Pinnacle master instructor is $250 for a 30-minute session. Volume discounts are available.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>About Pinnacle Performance Company</strong></div>\r\n<div>Pinnacle Performance Company provides individuals, from introverts to polished speakers, with the tools and techniques needed to become more influential communicators. By applying our innovative, three-step process, we show you how focusing on your message\'s objective and delivery will allow you to achieve specific audience reactions, captivate your audience and communicate like a true leader. &nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Pinnacle Performance Company&rsquo;s exclusive master instructors have trained thousands of business people worldwide, including CEOs, senior executives, professional speakers, sales people, trainers, engineers, customer service reps and more. Its client roster includes well recognized brands and blue chip companies like Allstate, Capgemini, Qualcomm, Walgreens, RR Donnelley, Oracle, Barclays, Underwriters Laboratories, Apple, IBM, Devon Energy, Spectra Energy, CITGO, Shell, Wells Fargo, KPMG, Emirates Airlines, Infosys and more.</div>', '1', 'en'),
(31, '2016-12-19 08:27:19', '2016-12-19 08:27:19', 1, 'events-tab', 'World HRD Resources Congress Awards Pinnacle Performance Company For Innovation In Learning', 'Pinnacle in the News', '<p><em>2013 Award is the fourth award in three years for the global communication skills training firm</em></p>\r\n<div><strong>July 16, 2013, CHICAGO</strong> &ndash; Pinnacle Performance Company added the 2013 Award for Innovation and Learning to its collection of World HRD Congress Awards. This is the fourth award in three years for the global communication skills training firm that applies acting technique to improve business professionals&rsquo; communication skills. This award joins 2012 awards for Best Training Provider and Innovation in Learning and a 2011 award for Vendor Innovation in Learning and Training Management.</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&ldquo;We set out to change how business professionals communicate, and we&rsquo;re thrilled organizations like the World HRD Congress are recognizing us for our innovative training program,&rdquo; said David Lewis, CEO and co-founder of Pinnacle Performance Company. &ldquo;We have trained in 30 countries, and global demand continues to grow, especially in Europe, India and Asia.&rdquo;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>The Excellence in Training and Development Award is organized by the Human Resources Development Management Committee of the World HRD Congress. It is the only award of its kind in India that honors individuals, teams and organizations from the corporate, education, public and private sector who leverage learning and development to significantly advance workforce productivity and performance. The third annual award ceremony was held on June 28, 2013 in Taj Lands End, Mumbai.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Several Indian organizations like Infosys, CapGemini and Virtusa trust Pinnacle Performance Company to help their emerging leaders, front line staff and senior executives improve, sharpen and hone their business communication skills.&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div><strong>About Pinnacle Performance Company</strong></div>\r\n<div>Pinnacle Performance Company provides individuals, from introverts to polished speakers, with the tools and techniques needed to become more influential communicators. By applying our innovative, three-step process, we show you how focusing on your message\'s objective and delivery will allow you to achieve specific audience reactions, captivate your audience and communicate like a true leader. &nbsp;&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div>Pinnacle Performance Company&rsquo;s exclusive master instructors have trained thousands of business people worldwide, including CEOs, senior executives, professional speakers, sales people, trainers, engineers, customer service reps and more. Its client roster includes well recognized brands and blue chip companies like Allstate, Capgemini, Qualcomm, Walgreens, RR Donnelley, Oracle, Barclays, Underwriters Laboratories, Apple, IBM, Devon Energy, Spectra Energy, CITGO, Shell, Wells Fargo, KPMG, Emirates Airlines, Infosys and more.</div>', '1', 'en'),
(32, '2016-12-19 08:29:06', '2016-12-19 08:29:06', 1, 'events-tab', 'Interview Of David Lewis In Dubai', 'Pinnacle in the News', '<p>Dubai: Richard Dean, David Lewis, CEO of Pinnacle Performance Company, and Amanda White discuss the importance of communication skills on the job.</p>\r\n<p><iframe style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border-style: none; display: block; width: 100%;" title="Audioboo player" src="http://audioboo.fm/boos/995724-david-lewis-07-10-2012/embed" name="audiobooframe1" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no"></iframe></p>', '1', 'en'),
(33, '2016-12-19 08:30:35', '2016-12-19 08:30:35', 1, 'events-tab', 'G. Riley Mills Joins Robert Thompson On His Blog Radio Show: Robert Thompson', 'Pinnacle in the News', '<p>G. Riley Mills, co-founder of Pinnacle Performance Company and co-author of The Pin Drop Principle, joins Robert Thompson and Mike Neiss to share how to captivate, influence, and communicate better using the time-tested methods of professional performers.</p>\r\n<p><object id="123412" name="123412" width="210" height="105" classid="clsid:D27CDB6E-AE6D-11cf-96B8-444553540000" codebase="http://download.adobe.com/pub/shockwave/cabs/flash/swflash.cab#version=9,0,0,0"><param name="movie" value="http://www.blogtalkradio.com/btrplayer.swf?file=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.blogtalkradio.com%2Frobert_thompson%2F2012%2F10%2F01%2Frobert-thompsons-thought-grenades%2Fplaylist.xml&amp;autostart=false&amp;bufferlength=5&amp;volume=80&amp;corner=rounded&amp;callback=http://www.blogtalkradio.com/flashplayercallback.aspx" /><param name="quality" value="high" /><param name="wmode" value="transparent" /><param name="menu" value="false" /><param name="allowScriptAccess" value="always" /><embed id="123412" src="http://www.blogtalkradio.com/btrplayer.swf" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" width="210" height="105" name="123412" /></object></p>\r\n<div style="font-size: 10px; text-align: center; width: 220px;">Listen to <a href="http://www.blogtalkradio.com">internet radio</a> with <a href="http://www.blogtalkradio.com/robert_thompson">Robert H Thompson</a> on Blog Talk Radio</div>', '1', 'en'),
(34, '2016-12-19 08:35:09', '2016-12-19 08:35:09', 1, 'events-tab', 'Co-author And Co-founder Of Pinnacle, Gary Mills Discusses How To Improve Communication With Steve Bertrand', 'Pinnacle in the News', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div id="nl_Kmao69E7FTqmIBP8" style="width: 550px; margin-top: 20px;"><a title="Author Gary Mills Discusses How to Improve Communication" href="http://www.newslook.com/videos/463427-author-gary-mills-discusses-how-to-improve-communication"><img src="http://img3.newslook.com/images/dyn/videos/463427/12/pad/550/410/463427.jpg" alt="Author Gary Mills Discusses How to Improve Communication" /></a>\r\n<div style="background: #efefef; border: 1px solid #ccc; color: #999; padding: 3px; text-align: right;"><a style="color: #999;" href="http://www.newslook.com/artsculture">Arts Video News</a> by NewsLook</div>\r\n</div>', '1', 'en'),
(35, '2016-12-19 08:37:04', '2016-12-19 08:37:04', 1, 'events-tab', 'Pinnacle Performance Company Earns Coveted International Award For Learning Innovation', 'Pinnacle in the News', '<p>The World Human Resources Development Congress and a jury of top executives, including the country\'s Secretary of the Department of Public Enterprises, recently presented Pinnacle Performance Company the prestigious award for Vendor Innovation in Learning and Talent Management. The award recognizes those companies believed to offer an exceptional approach to training and educational development.<img style="width: 200px; height: 274px; float: right; margin: 12px 8px;" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/StarTalLeadershipAward.jpg" alt="Pinnacle\'s Innovation Award" /></p>\r\n<p>After selecting Pinnacle from a field of Indian and international nominees, the award committee released this statement: "Pinnacle is an example of consistent innovation and has built uniqueness into its approach to training. This gives Pinnacle a competitive edge over others."</p>\r\n<p>Dr. Archana Arcot, Head of Organizational Development for India-based Infosys, a Pinnacle client since 2009, agreed with the Congress&rsquo; decision.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;The ability to understand the distinct leadership needs and then customize each program based on the specific target audience is what differentiates Pinnacle,&rdquo; reinforced Arcot. &ldquo;Their facilitators truly make the difference in terms of getting the learner into a deliberate practice frame that sustains itself beyond the program.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle has operated as a preferred communications training vendor for many Indian companies since 2005. Adding Asian clients to its international customer base (including 17 countries) proved a noteworthy challenge, but the company is encouraged by the Congress&rsquo; recognition.</p>\r\n<p>"We\'re ecstatic to receive this honor," said Dave Lewis, President and CEO of Pinnacle. "It validates our approach to training and encourages us to continue to chart new waters in international markets."</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle has trained thousands of international executives, managers and consultants and seeks to continue to expand its offerings into Dubai, Australia and Europe in 2011. Pinnacle would like to thank all of its international clients for helping make this possible!</p>', '1', 'en'),
(36, '2016-12-19 08:43:29', '2016-12-19 09:53:20', 1, 'events-tab', 'Introducing The Pinnacle Podcast', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="//www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" /></p>\r\n<p><strong>The Pinnacle Podcast</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Body Language</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Across the Globe</strong></p>\r\n<p>Is body language the universal language? Does it have grammar? The answer may surprise you. Brad and Spencer discuss the syntax of physical expression.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Play Podcast: <a href="http://email.robly.com/mpss/c/9wA/kEQeAA/t.1xa/GJoM9QIBSTGyEOMhlouEng/h5/trXlpRf87BxsDGhXkluuyIXLXZS9Mrmsond6mpwPuPRtP8Y1MbH6zlwGKQzhXGviJhtlc4Wy8ih-2FEut-2FFEq9PDAJbFgnEsQGtXI4OPDj3ELego3x-2FQ49o-2FhEDj3BiCXu8XMJYEMBwuA9vlimjezAJltrKeCmqH6o5nv79KwX2idtH-2FmLvvrMKeQzbUbt1m9-2FEuM2YmoQmBbUv10lzvRoSC7mspmp5SOaj-2FSqZzhGfzQ-3D" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Body Language Across the Globe</a></strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Introducing</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>The Pinnacle Podcast</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>The Science of Communication</strong></p>\r\n<p>Dear Loyal Readers,</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet would like to thank everyone that\'s written asking about its well-being and where it&rsquo;s been. Truth is, it&rsquo;s still here, and it&rsquo;s never been better! Red Carpet\'s been working on some new content and a few surprises, and we\'re excited to tell you about what\'s on the horizon.</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company prides itself on being innovative (we haven\'t won innovation awards four of the past five years for nothing). With the ways media and communication have been changing, Pinnacle is determined to stay on the cutting edge. Red Carpet is a part of that.</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet isn\'t disappearing, but it is transforming. Instead of solely existing as an electronic magazine, it will split into two different entities: the Pinnacle Podcast and the Pinnacle Blog.</p>\r\n<p><strong>The Pinnacle Podcast</strong>&mdash;We\'re always on the lookout for revealing research, fun factoids, and eye-catching curiosities about communication. Your hosts, Brad and Spencer, will look at it all through a light-hearted lens, so you can stay informed and impress your friends at parties. Just like with past Red Carpet issues, you\'ll receive notification of new podcast episodes through your email. You\'ll be able to stream the new episode right there, or download/listen to archived shows on our podcast page.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Listen to the Podcast here:</strong>&nbsp;<a href="https://vimeo.com/160934500?utm_content=67d3a6bad7b1679df7772c50fbc37cff&amp;utm_campaign=The%20Pinnacle%20Podcast%20Episode%201&amp;utm_source=Robly.com&amp;utm_medium=email" target="blanck"><span style="font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 17px;"><strong>Episode 1 - Is All We Have to Hear, Fear Itself?</strong></span></a></p>\r\n<p><strong>The Pinnacle Blog</strong>&mdash;This will be your source for noteworthy news and other timely events that won\'t fit in our Twitter account. The blog will be accessible from our home page and will focus on industry trends and other discoveries Pinnacle personnel make during the course of their work.</p>\r\n<p>Make no mistake, Pinnacle\'s still dedicated to delivering you the same informative, insightful, and entertaining content we always have&mdash;it will simply be in more modern formats.</p>\r\n<p>Thanks for being with us!</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet</p>', '1', 'en');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `category_id`, `alias`, `title`, `subtitle`, `content`, `visible`, `lang`) VALUES
(37, '2016-12-19 08:44:52', '2016-12-19 09:55:06', 1, 'events-tab', 'How DO You Lead A Horse To Water?', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 5 Issue 1</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">How <em>Do</em> You Lead a Horse to Water?</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 22px;"><strong style="font-size: 14px;">Unlocking the Secrets to Being Influential</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Charisma is a much sought after, yet elusive trait for many. It can difficult to describe on its own, but when encountering those that possess it, it is undeniable. They are the people that light up rooms, sway voters, or become figureheads. What makes certain people more influential and successful than others? Is charisma actually a skill that can be learned?</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle certainly believes so, and so do John Neffinger and Matthew Kohut, authors of <em>Compelling People: The Hidden Qualities That Make Us influential.</em> Unsurprisingly, Neffinger and Kohut make the case that others&rsquo; perceptions of you and your decisions are the most important factors in determining how successful and influential you are, oftentimes more important than the results of your actions. They make a strong argument for the power of confident, assertive body language and a level of self-awareness that aligns with the opinions of those around you. None of this should come as a shock to anyone that&rsquo;s participated in a Pinnacle workshop.</p>\r\n<p>What <em>is </em>fascinating about <em>Compelling People</em> is the authors distill &ldquo;influence&rdquo; down to two main qualities: <strong>strength </strong>and <strong>warmth</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>Strength, as defined in the book, is &ldquo;a person&rsquo;s capacity to make things happen with abilities and force of will.&rdquo; Productivity and accomplishment are powerful motivators, and strength demonstrates the capability to get results.</p>\r\n<p>Warmth is defined as &ldquo;the sense a person shares our feelings, interests, and view of the world.&rdquo; Essentially, we like people who are like us.</p>\r\n<p>Strength garners respect, warmth reaps support. When someone simultaneously projects both qualities, we look to them for leadership while investing our trust they have our best interests at heart.</p>\r\n<p>While examining many of the world&rsquo;s most influential people, it may be hard to describe these qualities in such concrete terms (like trying to describe a color); but that doesn&rsquo;t mean the effects are a complete mystery. Why then, when there are so many examples of influential people, is the combination of these two qualities so rare? The authors argue it is for two reasons:</p>\r\n<p><strong>Our self-perceptions don&rsquo;t match how others view us.</strong> Accurate self-awareness is a difficult boon to acquire. It requires much self-reflection, open-mindedness and objective critique. Many people already feel they possess the necessary qualities to be great leaders, but may, in the view of colleagues or friends, lack one or both of the above qualities.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Influence requires walking a fine line.</strong> Finding the sweet spot on the strength/warmth tightrope is difficult. Too strong and you&rsquo;re overbearing. Not strong enough and you&rsquo;re a pushover. Too warm and you seem too eager-to-please. Not warm enough and people think you&rsquo;re cold. Inhabiting the &ldquo;Goldilocks zone&rdquo; in the middle of both is a delicate balance.</p>\r\n<p>We know the Pinnacle Method works. It&rsquo;s been used, consciously and unconsciously, by influential people for millennia. <em>Compelling People</em> helps to further codify the cause and effect with observational science. Red Carpet recommends the book to anyone looking to gain more insight into being a better leader (after you read <em>The Pin Drop Principle</em>, of course).</p>', '1', 'en'),
(38, '2016-12-19 08:46:17', '2016-12-19 08:46:17', 1, 'events-tab', 'An Interview With Israel Antonio, US Para-triathlete Champion', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p>In the realm of athletic accomplishments, few garner more respect than the completion of a triathlon. Combining swimming, biking and running, the race is a true test of endurance, willpower, and character. Indeed, it\'s hard for Red Carpet to imagine training for a triathlon, let alone completing one.</p>\r\n<p>Imagine doing it while blind.</p>\r\n<p>Israel Antonio lost his sight when he was 14, but he has since accomplished more than many do in a lifetime. Pinnacle is co-sponsoring Israel\'s entry in the upcoming Paratriathlon World Competition in London, and he was kind enough to take a break from training to sit down for a Red Carpet interview.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Red Carpet:&nbsp;</strong>Hey, Israel, thanks for doing this. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Israel Antonio:&nbsp;</strong>My pleasure. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>I can barely walk a mile without passing out, so I think this is incredible. Aside from the obvious, what\'s your biggest challenge when doing these races? &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Swimming. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>Really? &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Yeah, I\'ve never learned to swim freestyle. I\'ve worked with several different instructors who insist I can swim, but I\'ve never felt comfortable or confident in the water. Prior to a race, sometimes I start having anxiety attacks.</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>What do you do?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>I take a few deep breaths before starting. I also had never learned to properly train until I reached out to Jenna Parker (<a href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?e=001rnlSnPlM_qzbt79JwtGQk1m_qSSL7i3XyfFCUfn1VtdubQd4n-dG--PLO94WBSRVCY3PE4nQFwRjQI_GCT6FLTTrrBptUf1BIUkvbkwyw-o72K-f8GsrP97gR2j7ZUx3" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">www.thejennaparker.com</a>). She\'s been helping me the last two seasons. I credit her for teaching me how to train smarter and race better.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>So Jenna\'s your trainer, and you also have a guide assisting you while you\'re actually racing?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Right. Someone to be my eyes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>Before the Chicago triathlon (August 23rd) your guide went down with an injury before the race. What went through your mind when you found out?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>My heart sank. Trust is the biggest aspect of the relationship with my guide. I feel they need to know what I do best and my shortcomings. I need to trust they will help me, especially through my anxiety in the swim. I had never raced with Dan (Daniel Tun, the injured guide), so the Chicago triathlon was an opportunity to learn about each other under race conditions. Since he was going to be my race guide for the World Championship in London, we needed Chicago to build that trust.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>Do you have a guide for London?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Yeah, Justin Sternberg. He helped me qualify for the 2013 Paratriathlon US Nationals. I am beyond excited that we\'re teaming up again.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>World Championship in London. This is the big time! What level of competition are you expecting?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>In my category, thirteen of the fastest totally blind males will race. I\'m hoping to stay close in the swim, then hammer hard on the bike and run. Knowing my swim is not good, I\'ve worked extremely hard to make my bike and run even stronger in case I need to chase down the others.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>Sounds like you know your game pretty well.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Absolutely. You have to. Above all, I just want to represent the United States to the best of my ability.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>What got you interested in triathlons in the first place?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Remember ABC\'s Wide World of Sports?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>With the Agony of Defeat skier?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Yeah. Well, there was an image of Julie Moss, crawling to the finish line of the 1982 Ironman Triathlon in Kona, Hawaii. At the time I didn\'t know what the Ironman was or why she was crawling, but the image stayed with me. When I got older I used to watch Fit Nation. I kept catching the same episode of Insider Training which featured Lokelani McMichael (the youngest person to complete the Ironman Triathlon.)&nbsp; Each time I\'d see the episode I\'d get more inspired, until I finally decided to see if a blind person could compete in triathlons.&nbsp; I discovered many had, so I decided to join their ranks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>And here you are, competing for the world championship.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>It\'s been a wild ride and a long road.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>A marathon, not a sprint, right? Or should I say triathlon?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>(laughs)&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>One last thing I ask all our guests. Pinnacle\'s fond of using thought-provoking quotes and maxims. Do you have one you\'d like to share?&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Paraphrasing a couple lines I learned from studying acting and movement with the beautiful and talented Laura Sturm: "Live in the moment with no regrets, no apologies."</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:&nbsp;</strong>Thanks, Israel. Best of luck in London.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>IA:&nbsp;</strong>Thanks!&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Israel Antonio is a successful playwright, screenwriter, actor, and triathlete.&nbsp; Israel\'s autobiographical piece,&nbsp;<em>In The Dark</em>, and short play,&nbsp;<em>Touch Of Rain: Praising Pulchritudinous Princess</em>, were critically acclaimed and audience loved.&nbsp;Israel made his triathlon debut at the 2008 New York City triathlon, and he continues to compete in marathons and triathlons across the globe.&nbsp;You can follow his blog at&nbsp;<a href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?e=001rnlSnPlM_qzbt79JwtGQk1m_qSSL7i3XyfFCUfn1VtdubQd4n-dG--PLO94WBSRVCY3PE4nQFwRjQI_GCT6FLXt4n32w9daEX8LWv8URXZ7Lh1K3VoDU5RDYhMHRww1F" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">http://sexyisra.blogspot.com</a>.&nbsp;Israel strives to have a lean physique similar to that of Bruce lee.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(39, '2016-12-19 08:48:13', '2016-12-19 09:55:31', 1, 'events-tab', 'Lost In Thought', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 4 Issue 6</p>\r\n<p>{poll}</p>\r\n<p><strong style="font-size: 24px;"><span style="color: #cc0000;">Lost in Thought</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>How to Keep Your Brain from Freezing</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>They go by many colorful names, including cramps, farts, and freezes, and that&rsquo;s just under the brain heading. Memory lapses. Senior moments. Those dreaded times when our minds fail us and we go blank. Murphy&rsquo;s Law dictates that it happen during a critical presentation or a high stakes conversation, whenever forgetting something you know like the back of your hand could do the most damage.</p>\r\n<p>What causes these annoying holes in our memory? Why does it often seem to happen at the worst possible time? How can we prevent them? Science and Red Carpet have the answer.</p>\r\n<p>Brain cramps are known among scientists as &ldquo;maladaptive brain activity changes,&rdquo; and there are two instances when they are likely to occur: extremely high pressure and extremely low pressure moments. In a previous article (available in our archives) Red Carpet talked about high pressure moments, and the difficulty our brains have when intently thinking about and focusing on tasks that should be highly autonomous. Low pressure moments are equally tricky to navigate, and the last thing any presenter wants is for a low pressure to suddenly become the opposite.</p>\r\n<p>To use an automotive metaphor, maladaptive brain activity changes is a fancy way of saying your brain&rsquo;s grinding gears. It&rsquo;s trying to switch between cognitive modes, and your mental transmission is getting stuck between speeds.</p>\r\n<p>Our brains are lazy. Whenever there&rsquo;s any chance to kick off the cerebral shoes and lounge around, it takes advantage of it. This occurs when performing a rote or routine activity (such as driving home from work or getting ready for bed) or in a moment where behavior is predictable (listening to a coworker drone on during a conference call). Like something out of an old Star Trek episode, our minds transfer power to critical systems to keep the ship running efficiently. While this transfer is taking place, there&rsquo;s a gap between our conscious and subconscious mind. If the timing&rsquo;s right (or should we say wrong?) and you happen to be thinking about something right then, there&rsquo;s a chance it might get lost in the gap. Sometimes things just fall through on their own. If you&rsquo;ve ever missed a turn driving home or forgotten something because you zoned out for a second, you&rsquo;ve experienced a maladaptive brain activity change, or brain fart.</p>\r\n<p>So how do we avoid being embarrassed by our brain&rsquo;s desire for a power nap? Science&rsquo;s best suggestion is to get your mind to ride the sweet spot between low and high stakes. Not so low that your brain goes on autopilot, but not so high that you obsess over every word you say. Pinnacle&rsquo;s concept of intention is actually a great solution, because it encourages you to rely on the reflexive preparation you&rsquo;ve done but also actively engage your audience so you never go passive. If there&rsquo;s one silver lining, it&rsquo;s that low stakes brain freezes are always isolated incidents. Once your mind realizes your mistake, it triggers an emergency startup sequence and goes on high alert.</p>\r\n<p>Ultimately, brain cramps are a great warning system. They let you know if you&rsquo;re taking something too seriously or not seriously enough without too much damage done. With good preparation and a relaxed approach, you&rsquo;re bound to keep your brain&rsquo;s temperature above freezing.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(40, '2016-12-19 08:52:00', '2016-12-19 09:55:43', 1, 'events-tab', 'In The Eye Of The Beholder: How Perception Of Stress Is Reality', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 4 Issue 5<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong style="font-size: 24px;"><span style="color: #cc0000;">In the Eye of the Beholder</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>How Perception of Stress is Reality</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>{poll} Sweaty palms. A racing heart. Your mind goes blank.</p>\r\n<p>Just a few of the common symptoms that trouble us whenever we step in front of an audience. The Fight or Flight response has a way of triggering at the worst possible time. What helped keep us alive millennia ago doesn&rsquo;t do much for us when we&rsquo;re standing in the board room. &ldquo;Flight&rdquo; is rarely an option is the professional world; and &ldquo;fight&rdquo; certainly won&rsquo;t get you that promotion you&rsquo;ve been after.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet has some bad news for you. Those sweaty palms aren&rsquo;t going anywhere. Your body has a vested interest in keeping you alive, so unless you can consciously control your nervous system you&rsquo;re in the same boat as 7 billion other people.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet also has some good news. While you can&rsquo;t directly change your body&rsquo;s reaction to perceived threats, you <em>can</em> change what your body <em>perceives to be a threat</em>.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The conversion of <em>distress </em>(bad stress) to <em>eustress </em>(good stress) really comes down to two things: preparation and perception. In Pinnacle workshops and elsewhere on this site we make a big deal about preparing properly. There are no magic words or secret techniques. Putting in the time practicing is one of the few surefire ways to increase your confidence.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Altering perceptions of a situation may be more difficult, but it can pay substantial dividends. In a recent study published in <em>Clinical Psychological Science</em>, subjects were asked to deliver a short talk detailing their strengths and weaknesses. Prior to the talk, half of the participants were encouraged to reinterpret their bodies&rsquo; threat responses as positive. Through verbal encouragement and the presentation of scientific studies on the benefits of stress, researchers did their best to reframe the participants&rsquo; perception of the event.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Those that received prior coaching demonstrated less of a threat response and also felt more comfortable with the symptoms they were experiencing. By simply changing how the speakers viewed their stress, it enhanced their confidence and helped them perform better.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Beauty may be in the eye of the beholder, but apparently so is our stress response. Our sympathetic nervous system has no reason to trigger if it doesn&rsquo;t perceive a threat. Combine preparation with an active attempt to embrace your distress as eustress, and your confidence and performance levels should both rise.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet encourages you to remember that the next time you&rsquo;re about to go caveman in front of the Board.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(41, '2016-12-19 08:53:15', '2016-12-19 09:55:55', 1, 'events-tab', 'Hold Em Or Fold Em?', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 4 Issue 4</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>{poll}</p>\r\n<p><strong style="font-size: 24px;"><span style="color: #cc0000;">Hold \'em or Fold \'em?</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>Penetrating the Impenetrable Poker Face</strong></span><br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>According to FBI interrogation techniques, the feet and legs of a suspect can be the most telling. A Stanford University study revealed that, of all the motions a poker player made, the way his arms pushed chips into the pot was the most predictive of the quality of his hand. Researchers at Princeton University found that, when shown pictures of a victorious athlete&rsquo;s face or body, subjects more accurately described the emotional context when viewing the body alone. What do these three instances tell us?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The face is not the first thing to observe when determining someone&rsquo;s true feelings.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If you think this sounds counterintuitive (Red Carpet agrees), you&rsquo;re not alone. In fact, when asked, most respondents <em>believe</em> they process another&rsquo;s feelings because of facial expressions, even if what&rsquo;s happening from the neck down has much more impact.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>That&rsquo;s not to say that facial expressions don&rsquo;t matter (they do!); it&rsquo;s that most adults have very good poker faces. One of the most important social skills we all possess is the ability to mask our feelings when we need/want to. If our faces betrayed our true feelings in every situation, imagine the awkward situations that would arise. Poker faces are a learned behavior that helps us survive in polite society.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>So how we do we learn to decipher the poker face so we can all move to Vegas and make millions? There are three main ideas to remember:<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Use the Whole Body.</strong> If you&rsquo;ve taken a Pinnacle workshop you&rsquo;re familiar with our philosophy on standing vs. sitting. Briefly, standing empowers you, as the communicator, with use of your entire instrument. Influencing others is a lot easier when you can bring to bear your entire arsenal of intention cues. Reading body language works the same way.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Gesture Rarely Has Specific Meaning.</strong> There are very few gestures in our repertoire that serve an isolated purpose. A handshake. A thumbs-up. A certain gesture made when someone cuts you off in traffic. Those all carry definitive, pre-defined meaning, but most gestures do not. Instead of thinking, &ldquo;He crossed his arms, so he must be defensive,&rdquo; more accuracy is found in the overall impression created by gestures and other physical cues.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>You&rsquo;re Already an Expert. </strong>You&rsquo;ve been reading body language your entire life and are a pro at reacting to it. Most of your decoding happens unconsciously, however, so it can be difficult to transfer those observations to the conscious mind. Listen to your gut. Ask it questions. With practice, you&rsquo;ll start to see and understand the intention cues that are affecting you.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet wishes you luck and hopes to see you on the next World Series of Poker. Just remember, if you win it all, Red Carpet gets ten percent.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(42, '2016-12-19 08:54:30', '2016-12-19 09:56:09', 1, 'events-tab', 'A Good Rule Of Um', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 4 Issue 3<br /> <br /> <strong style="font-size: 24px;"><span style="color: #cc0000;">A Good Rule of Um</span></strong></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>What Causes Verbal Trash and Why You Should Clean It Up</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><br /> Across continents, countries, and cultures, there is one phenomenon that proliferates communication: the inclusion of verbal fillers. Pinnacle diagnoses them as verbal viruses. Linguistic pathologists know them as <em>speech disfluencies</em>. No matter what you call them they are infectious and they are everywhere.</p>\r\n<p><br /> In the United States the common offenders are &ldquo;um&rdquo; and &ldquo;uh&rdquo; and, among youth, &ldquo;like.&rdquo; &nbsp;Russians call them &ldquo;vermin words&rdquo; and use the English equivalents of &ldquo;this&rdquo; and &ldquo;that.&rdquo; French speakers might use &ldquo;<em>quoi</em>,&rdquo; &ldquo;<em>bah</em>,&rdquo; or &ldquo;<em>ben</em>.&rdquo;American Sign Language even has a way to sign &ldquo;um.&rdquo;<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Why do we commit these sins of syntax? With their use being so widespread, is it possible they serve a productive purpose within our speech?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Researchers have multiple theories to explain why we insert these non-words into our everyday speech. The most obvious is that they are stalling mechanisms. When we are put in situations that call for impromptu speaking, we buy ourselves time to think and plot our semantic course by peppering our sentences with fillers.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Another explanation for speech disfluencies is that they are a verbal expression of nervous energy. We all give off body language cues (called <em>pacifiers</em>) indicating when we are uncomfortable. Fillers are an extension of that concept, only expressed through language.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Perhaps most interesting is the third theory, which paints verbal fillers as something that actually <em>benefits</em> the audience. Listeners need time to process incoming words and ideas. Verbal viruses allow for that occur while indicating the speaker has not completely finished. Fillers are nonverbal ellipses, while pauses are definitive periods, and some theorize that each has its own use.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet can hear you now. &ldquo;Uh, sounds like verbal fillers are a <em>good</em> thing. So, uh, why should I, like, get rid of them?&rdquo; Here&rsquo;s why.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>While it may be true that our brain&rsquo;s listening center does an excellent job of filtering out many fillers (listeners frequently report hearing only a fraction of a speaker&rsquo;s disfluencies), the efficacy decreases as the importance of the message increases. In other words, we listen more intently when we really care about what&rsquo;s being said. Generally speaking, audiences report verbal fillers as indicators of lack of confidence and preparation. In addition, any audience benefits to be gained from using them are only applicable in conversational situations, which most presentations are not.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>All is not lost. There are ways to eliminate and reduce the amount of interjectory sounds you&rsquo;re involuntarily producing. This month&rsquo;s Pinnacle Refresher will detail methods to cure the verbal virus contagion.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Until then, Red Carpet encourages you to&hellip;<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&hellip;pause.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(43, '2016-12-19 08:55:56', '2016-12-19 09:56:24', 1, 'events-tab', 'E-nough Is Enough', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 4 Issue 2<br /> {poll}</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">E-nough is Enough</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 14px;"><strong>Don\'t Let Your Communication Be a Casualty of the Digital Revolution</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>How many times have you checked your phone today? In the last 15 minutes? How may emails have you sent? Texts? You don&rsquo;t have to be a rocket scientist to notice that frequent face-to-face (and even ear-to-ear) communication is quickly becoming a thing of the past. Whether because of time pressure, distance or just plain convenience, instant, digital communication becomes more and more pervasive every year. What does that mean for our future as communicators, especially in the professional world?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>According to a 2011 University of Cambridge study, only half the respondents preferred face-to-face interactions to all other types, a significant decline from previous years. What&rsquo;s more, one third of those surveyed confessed to occasionally feeling overwhelmed and desiring escape from the pressures of technological communication. Professional environments exacerbate both numbers. Across the world, workers would rather email or SMS, but sometimes at the cost of their sanity.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>We love digital communication for obvious reasons: the speed and efficiency can&rsquo;t be beat; but the characteristics that make it appealing are also its biggest drawbacks. Sometimes speed and efficiency don&rsquo;t enhance communication&mdash;they worsen it.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Susan Tardanico, a communications coach and longtime executive consultant, believes we have &ldquo;exchanged quality for quantity&rdquo; when it comes to business communication. Essentially, the siren&rsquo;s call of saying more to more clients/coworkers is too much for people to resist, and people rarely stop to consider if it&rsquo;s the best way to get their message across (think about this the next time you&rsquo;re about to hit &ldquo;reply all&rdquo; on an email).</p>\r\n<p><br /> So how can we take advantage of all the benefits technology offers us without making others part of the 33% that feel overwhelmed? Here are some recommendations assembled from media and communications experts:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Think before pressing &ldquo;Send.&rdquo;</strong> If the email or text is a simple request/question/answer, then electronic communication is the way to go. If you think your email will lead to a lengthy chain, or if typing your message would take longer than an actual conversation, it might be time to call/talk to your recipient.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Connection is not conversation. </strong>Because of the ease of electronic communication it is also the most meaningless. For important messages or recipients, a conversation is almost always the right choice.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>When it doubt, talk it out.</strong> If you think there is any chance something you type could be misconstrued, talk instead. It&rsquo;s seemingly easier to electronically communicate about emotionally charged subjects, but it also heightens aggressive reactions. Proximity to people encourages level-headedness.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>No-tech times. </strong>Establish periods (even if they&rsquo;re brief), during meetings or communal lunches, when digital devices are switched off, no exceptions. Actively encourage others to contact you by means other than email and SMS. Experiment with increasing the amount of non-electronic communication you participate in and note how (if) it affects your productivity.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>By being more conscious about how we use technology, we can ensure digital devices enhance our communication, not substitute for it.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(44, '2016-12-19 08:57:04', '2016-12-19 09:56:39', 1, 'events-tab', 'An Interview With Karen Jaw-Madson', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 22px;"><span style="color: #b22222;"><strong>An Interview with Karen Jaw-Madson</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p>As a former HR director turned independent consultant, Karen Jaw-Madson has seemingly unlimited unique and knowledgeable perspectives on life and the professional world.&nbsp; Red Carpet has never left an encounter with her without wanting to learn more about <em>something</em>, and RC wagers you&rsquo;ll feel the same way after reading what she had to say. What follows is an excerpt&mdash;the entire interview is available in the Red Carpet archives.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Red Carpet: </strong>All right, Karen, here&rsquo;s your warm-up question. How do you define &ldquo;good communication skills&rdquo;?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Karen Jaw-Madson</strong>: Good communication skills require two things: effective preparation and intended outcome.&nbsp; Many people tend to focus on just the outcome of good communication, but I would argue that the preparation for the communication is even more important. That&rsquo;s where the real work happens.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: I know a lot of people who&rsquo;d say you just used a dirty word: preparation.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: (<em>laughs</em>)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: What gives with that?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: Most of us need some form of preparation, whether we like it or not. Even if it&rsquo;s just thinking and reflecting. Some are more dedicated than others, and the outcomes bear that out. Thoughtfulness and empathy are required to understand the audience and their needs, to select the appropriate tone, to organize the information properly, to choose the right words in the right amount of time, et cetera. All for a desired effect.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: I love hearing words like &ldquo;thoughtfulness&rdquo; and &ldquo;empathy.&rdquo; Our concept of intention is all about the &ldquo;how&rdquo; a message is delivered. It&rsquo;s all about the audience. Doesn&rsquo;t mean it&rsquo;s easy, though.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: (<em>smiles</em>)No way. We wouldn&rsquo;t have our jobs if it was.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: (<em>laughs</em>) <em>You</em> would. I&rsquo;d be blogging.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: I blog too!&nbsp; Good news is that it gets easier over time, and that being a good communicator pays off many times over.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Workplaces and HR are filled with jargon and buzz-phrases. &ldquo;Understanding your audience&rdquo; is one that gets tossed around a lot. What&rsquo;s your take?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: It&rsquo;s almost impossible to overestimate an audience&rsquo;s impact on your communication. Knowing their context should influence everything you do. Ignoring it can result in disaster. Are you familiar with design thinking?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Wait, who&rsquo;s asking the questions here?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: (<em>laughs</em>) It&rsquo;s relevant, I promise.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Hit me.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: Design thinking grew from designers taking a human-centered approach to developing desirable products and applying it more broadly to experiences in other contexts. For communication, this means putting the unmet needs of the audience above all else. Focusing on your audience&rsquo;s needs ensures the <em>design</em> of your communication will be relevant and impactful.&nbsp; There&rsquo;s lots of different ways of doing this, but keep in mind that:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>It&rsquo;s not about what you think, it&rsquo;s about what they think</li>\r\n<li>You should actually engage them</li>\r\n<li>It&rsquo;s not always what they tell you, but it&rsquo;s how they behave and why.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Sounds fascinating. I&rsquo;m going to Wikipedia that. (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_thinking">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Design_thinking</a>)</p>\r\n<p>You were an HR executive for a long time. What&rsquo;s a critical communication trait workplaces should be looking for when hiring?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: In all the hiring I&rsquo;ve done, regardless of the job level, I looked for whether the candidate could <em>discern </em>and<em>organize</em> what to say and how to say it as intended.&nbsp; No matter their job title, they would be representing a function, perspective, the organization, their employees, their co-workers, etc., and they would have to do it well.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Has anything changed now that you&rsquo;re an independent consultant?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: I look at the same criteria when choosing partners on a client&rsquo;s project.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s the same rationale&mdash;I have to be comfortable with a partner representing me.&nbsp; Evaluating communication style and skill in this different context is both affirming and interesting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: When you have multiple candidates that possess good communication skills, how do you differentiate?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: Differentiation happens when the skills are paired with authenticity.&nbsp; Communicating in a manner that aligns with your core values and your personal style builds credibility. The converse is also true&mdash;you risk losing credibility if you communicate in a way that isn&rsquo;t true to who you are.&nbsp; Audiences are very perceptive.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Any recommendation for someone seeking to boost their communication skill level?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>:A strong communicator should have a healthy dose of self-awareness so they not only understand themselves, but also how others might perceive them. If you&rsquo;re not sure how to go about doing this, get a communications coach or someone knowledgeable that will provide honest feedback.&nbsp; They can also prove to be invaluable in practicing your communication skills so you aren&rsquo;t going it alone.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: All right, last question, Karen. Pinnacle loves to use thought-provoking quotes in our materials. Do you have a favorite?</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: &ldquo;Our worlds are formed by the questions we ask.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Good one.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: There are different versions of this idea out there, but I attribute this quote to David Cooperrider. He introduced the concept of appreciative inquiry.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Something else to Wikipedia! (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appreciative_inquiry">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appreciative_inquiry</a>)</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: (<em>laughs</em>) It&rsquo;s an opportunities-based perspective and methodology for leveraging strengths for a better world. I love this quote because it&rsquo;s a reminder to be thoughtful about how we frame our questions, which in turn communicates our perspective and therefore creates our realities. That&rsquo;s powerful stuff if you ask me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: Indeed. Wow, Karen, I&rsquo;m leaving here excited and inspired to learn more about different ways of looking at communication.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: I&rsquo;m glad.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s my &ldquo;intention&rdquo; in the work that I do, to provoke new ways of looking at challenges and create opportunities that didn&rsquo;t exist before.&nbsp; In this way, I hope to make a positive difference in people&rsquo;s lives.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC</strong>: You&rsquo;re very good at it. Thanks so much for doing this.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>KJM</strong>: Any time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 11px;"><img style="width: 100px; height: 150px; float: left; margin-left: 5px; margin-right: 5px; border-width: 3px; border-style: solid;" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/Karen_Jaw-Madson2.jpg" alt="" />Karen Jaw-Madson left a successful career as a HR executive to pursue a &ldquo;portfolio career&rdquo; comprised of research, writing, consulting, teaching, and creative pursuits. In over 15 years of broad and diverse experience, she&rsquo;s been recognized as a versatile leader in both non-profit and corporate sectors, across multiple industries. Her responsibilities have included the development, leadership, and implementation of numerous organizational initiatives.&nbsp; These include change and turnaround projects, as well as talent and people strategies spanning many functional areas and across the globe.&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 11px;">As a people and culture strategist, Karen helps organizations design transformative experiences where both people and business thrive.&nbsp; Specialties include transformation strategies, employee engagement, organizational and talent sustainability, diversity and inclusion, and the application of design thinking to work experiences.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 11px;">Karen is breaking ground on her research in the design of work experiences.&nbsp; Find out more about her work and opportunities to collaborate at: <a href="http://www.designofworkexperience.com/">http://www.designofworkexperience.com</a> or contact her via LinkedIn.</span></p>', '1', 'en'),
(45, '2016-12-19 08:58:42', '2016-12-19 09:56:55', 1, 'events-tab', 'When In Rome...', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 4 Issue 1<br /> {poll}</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">When In Rome...</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><strong>How to Prevent Groupthink from Impacting Your Communication</strong></p>\r\n<p><br /> Have you ever worked with a team and found them hesitant to voice opinions when gathered? Or have you withheld your own views out of fear of being seen as unsupportive? If so, you have most likely encountered the negative repercussions of <em>groupthink</em>.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Groupthink occurs when individuals sacrifice their opinions and unique perspectives for the sake of consensus and self-preservation. In the business world, it is one of the largest barriers to open and effective communication.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>While much has been written about groupthink in the preceding decades, the foundational work began with Dr. Irving Janis&rsquo;s 1972 book, <em>Victims of Groupthink</em>.&nbsp; In it, Janis argues that many of history&rsquo;s notable disasters, from the atrocities of World War II to the Watergate scandal and beyond, could be attributed to groupthink. Specific motivators and circumstances become large inhibitors to communication, and it can be just as destructive on a personal level.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>How can we recognize groupthink when it&rsquo;s happening? How can we anticipate its occurrence? According to Janis and other psychologists, there are distinct characteristics/causes of a groupthink environment:<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>High Level of Cohesion.</strong> When a group is tightly knit and insulated from outside input, individuation is often at risk.&nbsp; The more homogenous a group is, the more likely it is for groupthink to take hold.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Strong, Partial Leadership.</strong> A leader&rsquo;s aggressive communication style combined with a strong bias will oftentimes do more than discourage group members from speaking out. Others may subconsciously realign their opinions to match that of the leader&rsquo;s.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>High Stress.</strong> The more threatened a group feels, by deadlines, failure or past experiences, the more likely it is to engage in groupthink. There is safety to be found in unanimity.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Once groupthink has taken root it can be difficult to dislodge. Changing group personnel and encouraging open feedback (even if it&rsquo;s anonymous) will sometimes work, as will just making the group aware of the situation.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If you think your team is being impacted by groupthink, here are some additional tactics to encourage individual expression:<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Assign a Devil&rsquo;s Advocate.</strong> Choose someone from within the group to do everything they can to find holes in the group&rsquo;s plan/decision/etc. With group support for rocking the boat, the individual will feel much less threatened.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>External Feedback.</strong> To minimize the one vs. many environment that can exacerbate groupthink, each member of the team must discuss the group&rsquo;s decisions with an outside source. That source&rsquo;s reactions must be brought to the group and evaluated objectively.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Contingencies.</strong> The group must agree upon one or two viable solutions/decisions in addition to the one being made. This will necessitate a broader range of opinions and discourage single-mindedness.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The effects of groupthink are subtle but powerful. By staying vigilant and take steps to reduce its impact and frequency, we&rsquo;ll all stand to be more productive and attend fewer meetings. And Red Carpet doesn&rsquo;t think it&rsquo;s groupthink for us all to agree that&rsquo;s a good thing.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(46, '2016-12-19 09:00:15', '2016-12-19 09:57:09', 1, 'events-tab', 'The Eyes Have It', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 3 Issue 6<br /> {poll}</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">The Eyes Have It </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Where You Look May Reveal What You\'re Thinking</strong></p>\r\n<p><em>&ldquo;The countenance is the portrait of the soul, and the eyes mark its intentions.&rdquo;<br /> Cicero</em></p>\r\n<p>A person&rsquo;s eyes are inarguably one of the most important factors in communication. Where they are focused, the duration of eye contact, the activity of muscles around them are just of few of the subtle signs that can reveal volumes about one&rsquo;s message and emotional state.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Proponents of the theory of neuro-linguistic programming (NLP) claim the eyes play a large role in revealing the innermost workings of the mind. You may have seen fictionalized examples of NLP on shows such as FOX&rsquo;s <em>Lie to Me </em>or TNT&rsquo;s <em>Leverage</em>. In short, NLP states how one moves his or her eyes when responding to a question might say a lot about the veracity of the reply.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>So Red Carpet is here to make you a better liar (possibly&hellip;nothing is 100% predictive, after all). In the diagram below are the six zones that NLP has charted as being the most commonly sought by a questionee&rsquo;s eyes. Monitor your own body language or stage some experiments of your own to verify if NLP theorists have it accurate.<br /> <br /> <img style="float: left;" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/face2.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="295" /></p>\r\n<p>1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Feeling/Kinesthetic</strong>&mdash;Smells, tastes and touches reside here. &ldquo;How were your mom&rsquo;s homemade cookies?&rdquo; would be a question that would prompt someone&rsquo;s eyes to go down and to their right.</p>\r\n<p>2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Auditory Constructed</strong>&mdash;Sounds that have to be imagined, either because they are artificial or have never been heard, reside here.</p>\r\n<p>3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Visually Constructed</strong>&mdash;Imagery that is created would drive the eyes here. &ldquo;Think of a pink rhinoceros.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>4)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Visually Remembered</strong>&mdash;When accessing primarily visual memories, our eyes go here.</p>\r\n<p>5)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <strong>Auditory Remembered</strong>&mdash;Spoken words or distinct aural cues bring our eyes to our immediate left. &ldquo;What did you and Sarah talk about?&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>6)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<strong> Internal Monologue</strong>&mdash;When talking to oneself or having extended periods of thought our eyes trend down and to our left.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Like many behavioral theories, NLP has its detractors, and many experiments have been done to debunk its findings. Red Carpet does not mean to present these theories as fact, but merely to show that fascinating research and ideas are continually being explored to unravel the mysteries of communication.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>What we can all agree on is that our eyes, oftentimes, say more than our mouths ever can. Whether you believe in neuro-linguistic or not, it&rsquo;s valuable to remember that one of the most important tools in any communicator&rsquo;s toolbox is the power of observation.</p>', '1', 'en');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `category_id`, `alias`, `title`, `subtitle`, `content`, `visible`, `lang`) VALUES
(47, '2016-12-19 09:02:16', '2016-12-19 09:57:24', 1, 'events-tab', 'Jung At Heart, Or Not', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 3 Issue 5</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">Jung at Heart, Or Not </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="font-size: 16px;">Why Communication Styles Aren\'t Black or White</span></strong></span><br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>{poll}As a people, we have a natural inclination to organize and categorize our lives. By qualifying and quantifying our experiences, we (theoretically) make it easier to understand the world around us and how to operate within its boundaries.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This desire to affix cognitive labels extends to people as well. It would be a rare find to locate someone who had not been categorized by a Myers-Briggs behavioral test or similar tool. Many of the character evaluation tools used today have their beginnings in the early and middle parts of the 20<sup>th</sup> century, and new research and writings are examining the ways we categorize the elusive thing called <em>personality</em>.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Two of the earliest, simplest and most familiar personality types are the <em>introvert </em>and <em>extravert</em>. Popularized by psychologist Carl Jung, those two terms are often misused and misunderstood today. Introversion and extraversion is a spectrum, and placing people firmly at one end or the other can be reductive and misleading, especially when it comes to communication styles.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Most people are <em>ambiverts</em>, falling somewhere in the middle of the spectrum. Look at the characteristics below and choose those that apply to you:<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Introvert&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Extravert</strong></p>\r\n<p>Prefer to express via writing&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prefer to express via speech<br /> Fewer but deeper interests&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Wide range of interests<br /> Thinks, then acts&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Acts, then reflects<br /> Needs alone time&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Needs time with others<br /> Pragmatic&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Risk-taker<br /> Concentrates easily&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Easily distracted<br /> Prefers lectures&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prefers seminars<br /> Often lets calls go to voicemail&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Answers almost every call<br /> Detail focused&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Big picture focused<br /> Prefers familiar surroundings&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Enjoys new environments<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If you are like most people, you probably selected the majority of one column with one or two from the other. Or you found yourself thinking, &ldquo;Well, sometimes I&rsquo;m like that, but other times I&rsquo;m the opposite.&rdquo; Either occurring is a good indicator that, like most people, you&rsquo;re an ambivert.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Personalities and communication preferences are tough to pigeonhole, no matter how much we like to classify things. Being self-aware and analyzing where those in your audience fall on the introversion/extraversion spectrum will help you tailor you message and become a more successful communicator.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(48, '2016-12-19 09:04:46', '2016-12-19 09:57:39', 1, 'events-tab', 'An Interview With ASTDs Dr. Jo Lynn Feinstein', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 3 Issue 5</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">In the Spotlight </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong>An Interview with ASTD\'s Dr. Jo Lynn Feinstein About the Challenges of Training Communication</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><br /> When it comes to professional communication, there are few people that know more about its methods and implications than Dr. Jo Lynn Feinstein of the American Society for Training and Development (ASTD). Red Carpet had the great fortune to sit down with her and get her unique perspective on communication and its impact within the field of Human Resources.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Red Carpet:</strong> As a coordinator of HR professionals, what defines &ldquo;good communication skills&rdquo; for you?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Jo Lynn Feinstein:</strong> In Neurolinguistic Programming there&rsquo;s a concept that the meaning of our communication is the response we get. Good communication elicits the response we&rsquo;re seeking. When we don&rsquo;t get the response we desire, we need to challenge ourselves to find a different approach.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:</strong> That sounds similar to our concept of intention. The idea of altering your delivery method to achieve a specific response from your audience.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF:</strong> It sounds very similar.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:</strong> In your experience, what&rsquo;s the most challenging aspect of incorporating communication training into learning and development?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF:</strong> Since everyone communicates every day, people think they already know all about it. Consequently, they aren&rsquo;t ready to learn. Building interest and enthusiasm becomes a prerequisite to actual learning.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC: </strong>Are most companies able to do this? Do they place the right amount of emphasis on communication as a skill?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF:</strong> Companies think their people know how to do this already, so they don&rsquo;t invest in developing this skill. Real communication is hard. We need to say what we mean, but say it in a way that the other person will understand, and be aware and considerate of the other&rsquo;s feelings. Think about your last disagreement. Was there a critical issue or was it the result of a misunderstanding?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:</strong> Uh, Red Carpet pleads the 5<sup>th</sup>.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF: </strong>(<em>laughs</em>)<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:</strong> As an ASTD coordinator, I&rsquo;m sure you&rsquo;ve seen a lot of great speakers. Is there one that particularly stands out for you?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF:</strong> Pinnacle&rsquo;s G. Riley Mills did a fantastic job at our recent LA chapter meeting.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC: </strong>Thanks for the unsolicited plug! (<em>whispers</em>) Your check is in the mail.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF: </strong>(<em>laughs</em>) No problem.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC: </strong>How has the emergence of technology redefined communication skills in the realm of Human Resources?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF:</strong> Technology&rsquo;s accelerated and enlarged the flow of information, and participants in learning activities have access to seemingly unlimited amounts of it. We need to be on our toes to make sure our information is current and meaningful, whether it&rsquo;s a learner in a training activity or a colleague on the job.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:</strong> Pinnacle&rsquo;s fond of using quotations throughout its materials. Do you have a favorite one you&rsquo;d like to leave us with?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF:</strong> &ldquo;<em>When the best leader&rsquo;s work is done the people will say, we did it ourselves!</em>&rdquo; &ndash;Lao Tzu<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If our interactions with those around us can engender this feeling of self-accomplishment, we&rsquo;ve been effective.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>RC:</strong> This has been great. Thanks so much!<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>JLF: </strong>My pleasure.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Dr. Jo Lynn Feinstein has been actively engaged in individual and organizational performance improvement for nearly 20 years. She has worked with public and private organizations, from startups to Fortune 500 companies.&nbsp; She holds a Doctorate in Organizational Leadership and an MBA. She was part of the pilot and among the first to earn the Certified Professional in Learning and Performance (CPLP) designation. Jo Lynn has been an invited speaker at conferences and workshops, and was recognized as Educator of the Year by the Ventura County Economic Development Association. She teaches graduate and undergraduate courses and serves on the Board of the Los Angeles Chapter of ASTD.</p>\r\n<p><br /> &nbsp;</p>', '1', 'en'),
(49, '2016-12-19 09:06:00', '2016-12-19 09:57:52', 1, 'events-tab', 'Getting The Juices Flowing', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 3 Issue 4</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">Getting the Juices Flowing </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p>{poll}</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="font-size: 16px;">How to Move Past Writer\'s Block</span></strong></span><br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>"I love being a writer.&nbsp; What I can\'t stand is the paperwork."</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Peter De Vries<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>It can last for mere minutes, or perhaps months. The harder you try to alleviate it, the worse it can become.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;What&rsquo;s wrong?&rdquo; someone asks.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;Nothing,&rdquo; you reply, exasperated. &ldquo;Absolutely nothing.&rdquo;<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><em>Nothing </em>is exactly what&rsquo;s wrong. You have writer&rsquo;s block.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Whether delivering a presentation, a keynote address or just trying to rock star some opening remarks, forcing creativity is a struggle for many. The blank screen or page is many a writer&rsquo;s nemesis. The problem is so prevalent, support groups exist, in both online and offline versions, to help writers break through the wall.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The causes are numerous. Whether it&rsquo;s fear of failure, being bored by a subject, the pressure of having to meet a deadline, or some combination of the above, each writer suffers in their own way.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Just as stage fright has no universal remedy, writer&rsquo;s block doesn&rsquo;t have a collective un-clogger. Culled from articles and interviews, here are Red Carpet&rsquo;s four best ways to burst the dam that&rsquo;s stopping your creative juices.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Start Where You Want. </strong>Just because your material has a beginning, middle and end doesn&rsquo;t mean you have to create it that order. Many writers take the opposite approach, crafting the conclusion first. It can be easier to know how something starts if you know where it&rsquo;s going. Ultimately, writing what part interests you most will make it less burdensome and may generate ideas for how to approach other sections.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Put <em>Something</em> On the Page. </strong>The scariest things about the blank page are the possibilities. It can go <em>anywhere</em>. Define some limits. Write one word, or a sentence that contains a core idea behind your content. Boundaries and direction may be the catalysts to get your brain moving.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lower Your Standards. </strong>Don&rsquo;t edit and compose at the same time. Worry about the perfect way to say it later. Shutting off your self-critiquing allows for more ideas to hit the page. Even if they don&rsquo;t make the final cut, they may lead to something worth holding onto.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Talk It Out. </strong>Grab your spouse or call a friend. Make sure you record it. Turning something from text into speech engages different parts of the brain and might knock a few extra ideas loose. Words that were eluding you may come more naturally if you force yourself to speak through it.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>These are great methods to use when approaching any creative endeavor, brainstorm or groupthink exercise, not just when preparing scripted material. Writer&rsquo;s block may not be avoidable, but a little mental grease can go a long way.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(50, '2016-12-19 09:08:08', '2016-12-19 09:58:05', 1, 'events-tab', 'Getting Out Of Your Own Way', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 3 Issue 3</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">Getting Out of Your Own Way&nbsp; </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="font-size: 16px;">The Science of How to Handle Pressure</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;You&rsquo;re just like everybody else<br /> Pressure!&rdquo;<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Billy Joel<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &ldquo;Pressure&rdquo;<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>If there&rsquo;s one experience everyone has had at some point in life, it&rsquo;s being in front of an audience (family, friends, colleagues, you name it) and choking. Maybe it was a presentation, or a three-foot putt, or your maid-of-honor remarks, but in spite of all your preparation and/or the fact you could do it in your sleep, you bombed it.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Why?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>In <em>Choke</em>, Dr. Sian Beilock investigates this curious phenomenon, details some fascinating findings and offers some concrete ways to handle pressure.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>{poll} The first mistake to <em>not </em>make is to associate your failure with a high amount of preparation (&ldquo;Things went so wrong&hellip;I must have prepared <em>too much!&rdquo;</em>). This wariness of over-preparation is one of the most frequently expressed concerns in Pinnacle workshops, and Dr. Beilock&rsquo;s research dispels the myth.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Ultimately, what fouls us up is the allocation of the brain&rsquo;s resources. High pressure situations usually mean we desire to control the outcome. In our attempt to ensure success, our awareness jumps to new heights and we focus on elements that would be better left on autopilot. Moving the subconscious (everything you prepared) into the conscious portion of the brain effectively nullifies work done to make it autonomous.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Have you ever had someone tell you to relax? If so, then you&rsquo;ve probably experienced a variation of the phenomenon we&rsquo;re talking about. As soon as you start <em>trying</em> to relax, the act of doing it becomes much more difficult.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>How can we prevent this from happening? Dr. Beilock has some suggestions:<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Don&rsquo;t Think About It.</strong> Easier said than done, Red Carpet knows. Essentially, distract yourself. Do something physically or mentally engaging (smartphones are great for this) prior to your pressure cooker to take your mind off of it. Trust yourself and let your preparation do its work.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Simulate Stress.</strong> Practicing your presentation in front of your spouse is much different than delivering it to a roomful of executives. The game-changer: the stakes are higher, the stress is greater. Find opportunities to practice under low-stakes pressure so performance stress becomes more tolerable.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Envision the Result.</strong> According to Beilock, focusing on the result of your actions helps trigger your body to use its practiced skills. For Pinnacle grads, this is synonymous with focusing on your intention. Concern yourself with your audience&rsquo;s reaction and let the content take care of itself.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Knowing the science behind the stress gives us the ability to make adjustments. Armed with a little more knowledge and a lot of preparation, you\'ll be better equipped to get out of your own way.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(51, '2016-12-19 09:12:34', '2016-12-19 09:58:19', 1, 'events-tab', 'Awarding The Pinnacle Oscar', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 3 Issue 2</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">And the Winner Is...&nbsp; </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="font-size: 16px;">Pinnacle\'s Favorite Movies of 2011</span></strong></span><br /> <br /> {poll} <span style="color: #000000;">The ballots are in. The statues have been awarded. Sean Young was arrested. Oscar has had his night.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">Around the Pinnacle offices, the only thing more fun than winning the annual office pool is participating in the trash talk. Red Carpet doesn\'t like to boast, but it turned in another strong showing placing second among the entire company. When will I learn to stop hitching my wagon to George Clooney?</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">Winning bragging rights is fun, but one of the most rewarding elements of Oscar weekend is finding diamonds in the rough. Pinnacle personnel love to swap personal Oscar picks, performances or films (touted or not) that should be recognized for strong, active, undeniable intentions. Being actors, we all love to talk acting. (Actually, it\'s less talk and more spirited debate, but that\'s semantics.)</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">Red Carpet wants to hear from you as well! Let us know what you think of our Pinnacle Top Five by voting in our Oscar-themed poll. Sore losers around the office need all the ammunition they can get.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000; font-size: 11pt;"><strong>Pinnacle\'s Top Five Films of 2011</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000; font-size: 11pt;"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">5) <em>The Ides of March</em>--The first of Clooney\'s films to appear on our list, <em>Ides</em> is great example of enacting complicated, subtle intentions. When secrets and corruption are involved, characters have no other choice.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">4) <em>The Iron Lady</em>--Worth watching primarily for Meryl Streep. Her portrayal of Thatcher is a clinic in physical and vocal transformation. <em>Lady</em> is a great example of how strong intentions can be pursued very subtly.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">3) <em>The Help</em>--Watching three different women forge a peculiar friendship amidst the personal and social challenges of the 1960s gives the audience a fantastic opportunity to witness constantly shifting intentions. Strongly acted all around.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">2) <em>The Descendants</em>--Like a Chekovian play, <em>Descendants</em> delicately walks the line between pathos and comedy. Clooney is at his best here, playing a still but slightly absurd family man struggling to find direction.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">1) <em>The Artist</em>--Like <em>The King\'s Speech</em> from last year, <em>Artist</em> was a shoe-in for the top spot. Silent movies require ironclad, specific and well-executed intentions to impact an audience, and Jean Dujardin\'s work is impeccable. Don\'t miss this one!</span></p>', '1', 'en'),
(52, '2016-12-19 09:13:46', '2016-12-19 09:58:31', 1, 'events-tab', 'Between A Rock And A Hard Place', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 3 Issue 1</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">Between a Rock and a Hard Place&nbsp; </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="font-size: 16px;">Primacy, Recency, and the Importance of Sequence</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">With the conclusion of 2011 and the arrival of the next year, Red Carpet thinks this is an appropriate time to talk about endings and beginnings and why they are important. Surely we\'ve all heard the maxims and imperatives surrounding the bookends of presentations: "You never get a second chance to make a first impression." "Finish strong!" Why is the largest portion of presentations, the 80% in the middle, so neglected by conventional wisdom? Why does no one ever tell you to "Make the middle count!"? &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">Perhaps there\'s just a shortage of pithy sayings, but there are also psychological reasons why this may be. Red Carpet kicks off the new year devoted to the concepts of primacy and recency and why they are important for communicators to remember.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">In the late 19th century, German experimental psychologist Hermann Ebbinghaus published On Memory, a collection of his research on cognitive retention. In the book he details what he describes as the serial position effect, or how the recollection of data depends upon the position of the data in a sequence. Try the experiment below:</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Study the list below for 15 seconds.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Without referring to the list, write the words you remember on a&nbsp;<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; separate sheet of paper.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Once you\'ve written all you can, continue reading.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span id="cke_bm_42S" style="display: none;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">PAR</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">CAD</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">DOG</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">ICE</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">ANT</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">BUR</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">EGG</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">JAM</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">MUD</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">POT</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">COP</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; margin-left: 120px;"><span style="color: #000000;">EAR<span id="cke_bm_42E" style="display: none;">&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">If you are like most people, the first few words on the list came with ease, the middle section was a little spotty, and the final two or three you recalled with no difficulty. If this was the case you have demonstrated Ebbinghaus\' theory of the primacy and recency. Observers and audiences are more likely to remember items and moments that bookend a given data set or experience. How can we make use of these theories when presenting?</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Synchronize content with primacy/recency.</strong> Ensure your critical points have a significant, unhampered presence near the front and back ends of your presentation. Combine this with other spotlighting techniques and your audience stands no chance of forgetting your key message elements.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Counteract the intermediate effect.</strong> Since retention is significantly reduced in the middle 40%, choose stronger, more active intentions to engage you audience. Make more liberal use of stories and other content texturizers to provide your audience with more memory points. Prioritize your messages and place the least important in the middle of your content sandwich.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Reduce distractors.</strong> Ebbinghaus notes that the introduction of distractions (Red Carpet\'s looking at you, PowerPoint) severely impacts primacy and recency. Don\'t sabotage yourself with unneeded areas of focus (see Red Carpet Volume 2, Issue 4, available in the archives).</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="color: #000000;">Understanding the science behind first and last impressions will help make us superior communicators and allow us to better shape our content and influence our audiences.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #000000;">Now, if only Red Carpet could shed those holiday pounds...</span></p>', '1', 'en'),
(53, '2016-12-19 09:15:53', '2016-12-19 09:58:43', 1, 'events-tab', 'Always Leave Em Wanting More', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 2 Issue 9</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">Always Leave \'Em Wanting More&nbsp; </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong>Content, Cutting and Message Clarity </strong></span></span></span><br /> {poll}</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo;I try to leave out the parts that people skip.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Leonard Elmore, novelist<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>One of the most difficult parts of cobbling together a presentation is deciding what material to keep and what to discard. Presenters usually find themselves in the position of having to convey a lot of new information in a very short period of time (i.e. sales calls, project updates). The natural inclination is to include exhaustive details, to fully plumb the depths of the given topic and leave no stone unturned. &ldquo;How is client X supposed to realize how great our company is unless I tell him all about it?&rdquo; &ldquo;How is my team to make decisions without knowing the intricacies of our project?&rdquo; More information means greater understanding, right? Wrong. And Red Carpet is here to tell you why.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>What did you do last weekend?<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>A simple question that isn&rsquo;t so simple to answer. Sure, you might be able to recount major events (went to the movies, had the family over, took the kids to a birthday party), but moments outside those &ldquo;markers&rdquo; would be more difficult to recall. Our brains do an excellent job of filtering out mundane details. In order to preserve energy, save us headaches and reserve resources for higher cognitive functions, they look for opportunities to go on autopilot. Routine activities typically trigger this somatic automation. We&rsquo;ve done certain things so many times before, as soon as our brains recognize the patterned behavior, <em>click!</em>, we go on autopilot.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The identical result occurs when confronted with too much information. Our brains search for the aforementioned markers, something that stands out amidst the white noise. If too much material is thrown at an audience, there is a dilution of what&rsquo;s important. In essence, everything becomes mundane, and their autopilots begin to activate.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Red Carpet has written in past newsletters about attention spans and maximizing retention rates. Content selection is another face of that many-sided coin. &ldquo;Less is more&rdquo; is an oft-repeated clich&eacute; that contains truth but offers no practical answers. What is one to do? Here are three simple guidelines that will help you distill your content:<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Pick Three.</strong> Limit yourself to three major ideas/concepts/points. <em>No more</em>. One of the hardest things to do as a playwright, screenwriter or author is make cuts. &ldquo;There&rsquo;s so much good info!&rdquo; No, there isn&rsquo;t. &ldquo;All these details are important!&rdquo; No, they&rsquo;re not. Make hard choices about what stays and what goes. If you&rsquo;re having a hard time being objective, involve someone else. Another set of eyes and ears can be invaluable.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Start Small.</strong> If you&rsquo;ve been allotted time to present, don&rsquo;t plan on using every second. Challenge yourself to be as concise as possible. What would your presentation look like if you <em>had </em>to deliver it in five minutes? How about ten? Fifteen? Instead of trying to whittle everything down to fit your given timeframe, build your presentation in reverse by gradual addition. Stop when you reach 75-80% of your time allotment.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>WIDLIO.</strong> Syntax artists may recognize this acronym: <strong>W</strong>hen <strong>I</strong>n <strong>D</strong>oubt, <strong>L</strong>eave <strong>I</strong>t <strong>O</strong>ut. While English teachers may have had commas in mind when devising this mnemonic device, it can apply to content as well. Apply those scissors liberally. Make certain you rank the contents of your cutting room floor. If you change your mind or need to add more at a later date, knowing what almost made the grade will be valuable.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The urge for a presenter to &ldquo;show up and throw up&rdquo; every little detail can be difficult to resist. By distilling your content down and skimming the cream, you not only reduce audience distractions but also gain more control over what they retain. A bit of extra effort and some hard choices can make &ldquo;less is more&rdquo; truly win/win.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(54, '2016-12-19 09:17:10', '2016-12-19 09:58:54', 1, 'events-tab', 'Fight Or Flight Makes Right', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 2 Issue 8</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">Fight or Flight Makes Right&nbsp; </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong>How Stage Fright Keeps You Safe</strong></span></span></span><br /> <br /> <br /> {poll}Betrayed by their bodies.<br /> <br /> That is how many describe the experience of stage fright. Over the centuries, our brains have learned how to cope with a variety of stimuli and situations. One of the strongest reactions we can experience is what is commonly known as &ldquo;fight or flight.&rdquo; Simply put, it is our body&rsquo;s automatic response to a perceived threat. Across cultures, continents and the animal kingdom, the reaction is uniform&mdash;whether it is prey fleeing a predator or you presenting at a high stakes meeting.<br /> <br /> Unfortunately, while human civilization has evolved, our biochemistry remains firmly rooted in the Stone Age. While we&rsquo;re thinking &ldquo;boardroom,&rdquo; our bodies are screaming &ldquo;<em>bail out!</em>&rdquo; What causes such an acute reaction? And what exactly is happening to make us feel so <em>nervous</em>? Red Carpet has the answers.<br /> <br /> It may be odd to think that our brains are actually trying to do us a favor when we experience stage fright. Our mind has identified a situation which poses a threat, and it wants to protect us. Unfortunately there is no discrimination between physical and emotional threats, so we react staring to down a room of executives as we would to being chased by a hungry bear. The expectations of professional decorum make it difficult to take advantage of the body&rsquo;s stress response.<br /> <br /> There are multiple triggers as your brain preps your body for action.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Breathing quickens and heart rate accelerates.</strong> To ensure the body has enough oxygen to power the expected increase in activity, the lungs and heart go into overdrive. This is why your heart pounds, your face flushes and breathing becomes difficult.<br /> <br /> <strong>Muscles tense and sweat glands start pumping. </strong>These are primarily for the &ldquo;fight&rdquo; half of the stress response. Tension provides more power for hand to hand combat and more sweat means an increased cooling factor.<br /> <br /> <strong>Butterflies, the jitters and altered perception.</strong> These are primarily for the &ldquo;flight&rdquo; response. The brain opens the adrenalin and epinephrine floodgates, and our bloodstreams fill with energizing hormones. It feels good to move because our brain is screaming, &ldquo;<em>run!</em>&rdquo; Increased alertness means changes in how we perceive the passage of time.<br /> <br /> In addition, our body starts to shut down non-essential functions: digestion slows as blood is diverted elsewhere, salivary glands become inhibited (dry mouth) and bladder and bowel muscles slacken (the pervasive feeling of having to go to the bathroom).<br /> <br /> The most important thing to remember while all these symptoms are manifesting is that <em>you always feel more nervous than you appear. </em>That may be small consolation when your heart is pounding and you feel like vomiting, but many expressions of stage fright can be surprisingly subtle and nearly invisible, especially in large venues. Once your mind realizes the threat isn&rsquo;t immediate (hopefully a few minutes into your presentation), it will reduce the stress response and symptoms will mostly disappear.<br /> <br /> Stress responses manifest in the body but originate in the mind. The battle to tackle stage fright is mostly mental and can be largely won with proper preparation combined with the other techniques Pinnacle has given you. Remember that reduction of symptoms, not elimination, is the goal, and you&rsquo;re halfway toward being a more calm and confident communicator.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(55, '2016-12-19 09:19:47', '2016-12-19 09:59:06', 1, 'events-tab', 'Reducing The Cost Of Paying Attention', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 2 Issue 7</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">Reducing the Cost of Paying Attention&nbsp; </span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; line-height: normal; font-style: normal; font-family: Arial Black,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; color: #000000; font-size: 11pt; font-weight: normal; text-align: left;" align="left"><span style="font-size: 12px;">{poll}</span><span style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong>How to Increase Your Audience\'s Attention Span</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; line-height: normal; font-style: normal; font-family: Arial Black,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; color: #000000; font-size: 11pt; font-weight: normal; text-align: left;" align="left">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">"<em>I sometimes worry about my short attention span, but not for long."</em></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -Herb Caen</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">There is little debate that our attention spans are growing shorter with each passing year. While Red Carpet is certain most people would award on-demand entertainment and the internet mostly positive marks, every rose has its proverbial thorn. The ability to stream what we want when we want it and the power to switch web pages instantly grants us more control over how we occupy our time, and, inevitably, there are repercussions when we lose that control.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">Gone are the days of the Lincoln-Douglas debates, the Illinois senatorial contests of 1858, where audience members listened in rapt attention, on many occasions, for over <em>three hours</em>. Accessibility and convenience are the watchwords of modern entertainment, and the paradigm shift has had an impact on the modern presenter.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">While the numbers vary on the exact amount of time it takes for an audience\'s attention to wander, much of it depends on the type of attention being applied:</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><em>Focused attention - </em>the type of attention we pay sudden stimuli (a loud noise, quick movement in our peripheral vision, etc.). The maximum span for this type of occurrence is only a few seconds.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><em>Sustained attention</em> - the type of attention that requires voluntary commitment (movies, conversations, presentations, etc.). Most adults have a maximum attention span of 20 minutes before having to renew it.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">Twenty minutes is not much time. That number also does not account for many of the obstacles working against a presenter (fatigue, hunger, stress, etc.), so it is fair to say a presenter shouldn\'t rely on it.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">Researchers also found attention spans lengthened and were renewed more often when audiences:</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="margin-left: 0.5in; color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">1)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; did something they enjoyed or</p>\r\n<p style="margin-left: 0.5in; color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">2)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; were intrinsically motivated.</p>\r\n<p style="margin-left: 0.25in; color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">Since the first is a no-brainer, Red Carpet will focus on the second item. "Intrinsic motivation" is another way of saying "investment in the outcome." How does a presenter encourage her audience to invest in what she has to say? The answer lies in hooks.<br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #000000;">Hooks are unique attention grabbers meant to reel in your audience. They encourage the investment mentioned above because they appeal to audiences on multiple levels. Your Pinnacle training and manual discussed hooks, but here are some more advanced elements to keep in mind.</span><br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Use early, use often.</strong> Hooks work well as early attention grabbers, but don&rsquo;t be afraid to sprinkle them throughout. Some work well as bookends or can be doled in segments. As mentioned earlier, 20 minutes is the most you can expect from people, so you may have to continually hook them.</span><br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Don&rsquo;t steal your own thunder. </strong>Stories and other hooks that have climaxes can be tricky. The payoff must be proportional to the time spent building it up. That said, resist the urge to give away the gold early. An aura of mystery and teasing the audience with the conclusion is a great way to keep them intellectually and emotionally invested.</span><br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #000000;"><strong>Multiple points, multiple hooks.</strong> Resist the urge to overuse one type of hook. If you started off with a story, throw in a quote or an interesting statistic. Challenge your audience in different ways at different times to maximize their investment level.</span><br /> &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="color: #000000;">Hooks are often viewed as ancillary, an add-on to the &ldquo;meat&rdquo; of a presentation, but they provide ways to inject personality into an often stale event. Red Carpet encourages you to remember that, without your audience&rsquo;s attention, premier content will accomplish very little. Hook them early and don&rsquo;t let them go.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-size: 8px;">Sources available upon request.</span></span></p>', '1', 'en');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `category_id`, `alias`, `title`, `subtitle`, `content`, `visible`, `lang`) VALUES
(56, '2016-12-19 09:21:29', '2016-12-19 09:59:18', 1, 'events-tab', 'Finding Your Way Outside The Box', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 2 Issue 6</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 24px;"><strong><span style="color: #cc0000;">Finding Your Way Outside the Box &nbsp;</span></strong></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; line-height: normal; font-style: normal; font-family: Arial Black,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; color: #000000; font-size: 11pt; font-weight: normal; text-align: left;" align="left"><span style="font-size: 16px;"><span style="color: #000000;"><span style="font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong>Breaking Down the Barriers to Creativity</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 0pt; line-height: normal; font-style: normal; font-family: Arial Black,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif; color: #000000; font-size: 11pt; font-weight: normal; text-align: left;" align="left">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">Inspiration can be one of the most elusive things. Even for those professionally involved in creative fields, the spark of creativity can often remain just out of reach. For many presenters, one of the most frequent challenges is finding new and innovative ways to approach dry material. Indeed, if you are not one who thinks of him/herself as a creative person, the task becomes doubly difficult. Red Carpet is here to help classify your creativity and break down the walls that inhibit your inspirational catalysts.</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">Creativity means much more than simply generating something from nothing. Creative people oftentimes view the world through a different lens and think about it in different ways than others. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">One of the most common theories to explain this phenomenon is <em>brain lateralization</em>. (People that describe themselves as "right or left-brained" are promoting this theory, whether they know it or not.) Brain lateralization states that humans use the halves of their brains for different functions and that, generally speaking, creative people use the right side of their brain more often. &nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 14px;">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">By reviewing the columns below, tally how many times you match the given associations. If you don\'t fit one, give yourself a point for the opposing side. Observe where you fall on the lateralization spectrum: left, right or in the middle?</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #ffffff; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; text-align: left; margin-left: 60px;" align="left"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px; text-align: left; margin-left: 60px;" align="left"><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>LEFT SIDE</strong></span><strong> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>RIGHT SIDE</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prefers verbal instructions&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Prefers fiction to non-fiction</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Uses outlines and structure&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Relies on intuition more than logic</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Enjoys reading&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Cat lovers</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Good at math &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; More focused on concept than detail</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Enjoys classical music &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Likes working in a group</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><span style="font-size: 12px;">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Thinks best while sitting&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; Gestures frequently</span></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 12px;">For a more complete and detailed analysis, take this <a style="color: blue ! important; text-decoration: underline ! important;" href="http://www.wherecreativitygoestoschool.com/vancouver/left_right/rb_test.htm" shape="rect">test</a> provided by the Art Institute of Vancouver.<br /> &nbsp;<br /> On which side did you predominantly fall? Most people land somewhere in the middle, with tendencies toward the left side of the brain.<br /> <br /> Creativity for most of us, to simplify things a great deal, means thinking about things in ways we are not accustomed. By nudging our brains outside their normal patterns of cognition, we engage powerful (but often neglected) resources.<br /> <br /> Below are some ways to more actively engage the right side of your brain. Use these when seeking a new approach to dull material, to catalyze more personal creativity or to simply alleviate a bad case of writer&rsquo;s block. Thinking outside the box becomes much easier when you&rsquo;re never inside it in the first place.<br /> <span style="font-size: 18px;">&nbsp;</span><br /> <strong>Redefine Your Audience&mdash;</strong>We present and speak to the same people in the same environment so often it causes our approach to become static. How would things change if you presented to children? To your family? How does a new audience alter your perspective?</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 12px;"><strong>Record Yourself&mdash;</strong>Without editing yourself, speak into a recording device about your ideas, obstacles, anything that comes to mind. Activating speech and language centers encourages more of your brain to attack any problems. Listen to playback.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 12px;"><strong>Change Your Physical Position&mdash;</strong>Look at something from a different angle, literally. Get up, move around, change locations, exercise. Right-brained people are typically very animated. Combining thought with physical activity will encourage both sides of your brain to work in conjunction.</span></p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 12px;"><span style="font-size: 8px;">Sources available upon request.</span></span></p>', '1', 'en'),
(57, '2016-12-19 09:24:11', '2016-12-19 09:59:31', 1, 'events-tab', 'Presenting In A VAKuum', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 2 Issue 5</p>\r\n<h1 style="color: #cc0000;"><span style="color: #ff0000;">Presenting in a VAKuum</span><br /> <span style="font-size: 14pt; color: #000000;"><span style="font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif;"><strong>How Learning Styles Can Make You More Effective</strong></span> &nbsp;</span></h1>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">{poll}Every presenter has a responsibility to do her best to maximize information retention. This is especially important for those that deal with highly technical material or fill the role of an instructor. Pinnacle graduates know the best way to ensure their audiences remember what\'s important is to keep them engaged with a strong intention and proficient application of our core building blocks. But what else can one do? What additional methods can a presenter utilize to make the most of time spent in front of an audience?</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">Educators have known for many years that not all students respond identically to classroom stimuli. While there are many differing theories concerning how people learn, one of the most commonly accepted and frequently cited is VAK (Visual/Auditory/Kinesthetic).</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">Pioneered in the 1920s and further evolved and adapted by Neil Fleming and others, the VAK distinctions can be a boon for a savvy presenter. VAK proponents hold that each person assimilates and processes information in a preferred manner. Presenters that know their audience can skew their presentations toward a certain learning style. Presenters that regularly deal with new audiences should include a variety of "carriers" for their information.</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><strong>VAK Breakdown and How to Use the Styles</strong></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><strong>Visual</strong> (preferred by 65% of the population)</p>\r\n<p style="color: #000000; margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">As any Pinnacle grad knows, visual components tend to resonate the most with audiences, and the VAK theory supports that conclusion. When in doubt, assume your audience is composed of primarily visual learners.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style="color: #000000;">Memory is enhanced by pictures. Use visual aids that feature images instead of text.</li>\r\n<li style="color: #000000;">Prefer to see the whole concept instead of individual parts. Be sure to present the "big picture."</li>\r\n<li style="color: #000000;">Colors tend to leave a lasting impression. Use them strategically.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Auditory</strong> (20% of the population)</p>\r\n<p>These people, not surprisingly, tend to be talkative. Books on tape and a healthy appreciation for lectures are the hallmarks of an auditory preference.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Memory is enhanced by discussions and open forum debates. Pose questions to these people and solicit their opinions.</li>\r\n<li>Need time to reflect and consider. Be certain to include time for review/summary at the end of your presentation.</li>\r\n<li>Gains limited benefit from reading. Restrict the amount of supplementary written material you provide.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Kinesthetic</strong> (15% of the population)</p>\r\n<p>The toughest to cater to in a corporate environment, kinesthetic learners process information through touch and experimentation. They love to get &ldquo;hands on&rdquo; and many enjoy presenting.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Memory is enhanced by engaging in activity. Try to include props or other tactile representations of concepts/info.</li>\r\n<li>Become bored with traditional presentations quickly. Keep things moving and try not to be predictable.</li>\r\n<li>Unconsciously fidgets. This does not necessarily mean you are boring them. They&rsquo;re bodies are anxious to <em>do </em>something.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The University of South Dakota provides a questionnaire that will assess your own learning style. (<a href="http://people.usd.edu/%7Ebwjames/tut/learning-style/stylest.html">http://people.usd.edu/~bwjames/tut/learning-style/stylest.html</a>)</p>\r\n<p>By becoming more aware of how your audience processes information, you can customize your delivery to maximize retention and keep them in the palm of your hand.</p>\r\n<p><span style="font-size: 8px;">Sources available upon request.</span></p>', '1', 'en'),
(58, '2016-12-19 09:27:19', '2016-12-19 09:59:59', 1, 'events-tab', 'What\'s The (Power)Point?', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /></p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company&nbsp; www.pinper.com&nbsp;&nbsp; Volume 2 Issue 4</p>\r\n<h1 style="color: #cc0000;"><span style="color: #ff0000;">What\'s the (Power)Point?</span></h1>\r\n<p>Along with advances in technology come tools designed to make our lives easier, increase productivity and generally make what we are already doing more effective. The flip side to this phenomenon is that, if not used correctly, these same tools can actually do the opposite.</p>\r\n<p>In the world of professional presentations, PowerPoint is king. First debuting in 1987 as a program called "Presenter," the version that revolutionized the workplace did not appear until ten years later. It has been a staple, for better or worse, of boardrooms, lecture halls and meetings ever since.</p>\r\n<p>"Without a doubt, across continents, cultures, and businesses, one of the most misunderstood tools in the professional arsenal is PowerPoint," says Pinnacle co-founder, Gary Mills.</p>\r\n<p>He is not alone in this belief. Hundreds of websites (www.beyondbulletpoints.com), books (<em>Cutting Edge PowerPoint for Dummies</em>) and, ironically, PowerPoint "decks" have been created to help the uninitiated master the slide-creating software. Catchphrases such as "PowerPoint Hell" and "PowerPoint Poisoning" are now a part of the professional vernacular. How can one tool be so embedded in professional culture, yet be so misunderstood? How can one avoid the common missteps that plague so many presentations?</p>\r\n<p>"Microsoft will teach you how to use Word, but not how to be a writer," analogizes Roger Courville, author of <em>The Virtual Presenter\'s Handbook</em>. While his point is more directed toward webinars and other forms of virtual communication, the idea is applicable toward PowerPoint. A misunderstanding of the medium and how it should be used is the underlying culprit.</p>\r\n<p>At some point since its inception, PowerPoint became more than a visual supplement. Ellen Finkelstein, author of <em>101 Advanced Techniques Every PowerPoint User Should Know</em><em>, believes it started in academia. </em></p>\r\n<p>"When PowerPoint emerged, professors used it as a substitute not only for what they had written on the blackboard (whiteboard, by that time), but for their notes. Now they didn\'t have to write on the board each class, and they didn\'t have to read from their notes. They could show the students more of their notes!"</p>\r\n<p>Finkelstein makes the case that presenters today are only repeating what they have seen. Bad lectures in school and bad presentations in the boardroom beget more of the same. PowerPoint is oftentimes being used in ways for which it was never designed: as a substitution for documents and a catalogue of minutia.</p>\r\n<p>How can one avoid PowerPoint pitfalls?</p>\r\n<p><strong>Embrace the Medium</strong>-PowerPoint is a visual tool, so use images instead of text whenever possible. The idea that A Picture is Worth a Thousand Words means your audience will absorb broader topics and concepts quicker, and it will prevent you from getting bogged down in unnecessary details.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Keep It Simple</strong>-Reduce the number of slides and the amount of text on the slides as much as possible. There is a difference between "Need-to-Know" and "Need-to-Show." The audience will spend more time listening and less time reading.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Be Aesthetically Sensible</strong>-Be conscious of colors, fonts, type sizes, backgrounds, etc. Remain stylistically consistent with how your slides appear. Oftentimes, colors and text size can change from computer to projector, so double check your technology.</p>\r\n<p>For more information on this topic, Red Carpet encourages you to read the essays of Edward Tufte. Red Carpet also recommends <em>The Wall Street Journal Guide to Information Graphics</em> by Dona M. Wong for those that work with statistics, tables and charts on a regular basis.</p>\r\n<p>By changing perspectives on Microsoft\'s workplace warhorse, hopefully we can change the presentation paradigm and administer the antidote to PowerPoint Poisoning.</p>', '1', 'en'),
(59, '2016-12-19 09:28:46', '2016-12-19 09:28:46', 1, 'events-tab', 'Online Meeting Resources Recommendations', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<p>Many companies provide resources for enhancing virtual meetings. However, when looking for that tool to collaborate with meeting attendees or to share the visual portion of a message we\'ve put together a short list of virtual meeting resources</p>', '1', 'en'),
(60, '2016-12-19 09:30:45', '2016-12-19 10:10:18', 1, 'events-tab', 'The Memory Game – Improving Learning Retention', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><img class="img-responsive" src="http://www.pinper.com/webroot/media/images/redccarpet.jpg" align="none" /><br />\r\n<h5>Pinnacle Performance Company www.pinper.com Volume 2 | Issue 3</h5>\r\n<br />\r\n<h4>The Memory Game - Improving Learning Retention</h4>\r\n<h2><canvas width="53" height="21">The </canvas><canvas width="93" height="21">Memory </canvas><canvas width="70" height="21">Game </canvas><canvas width="21" height="21">&ndash; </canvas><canvas width="108" height="21">Improving </canvas><canvas width="96" height="21">Learning </canvas><canvas width="91" height="21">Retentio</canvas></h2>\r\n<p>How many times do you forget where you put your car keys? Or do you forget why you walked into the kitchen? Our memories can be tricky to manage. We want to believe that what we put in them is stored safely, and when we cannot retrieve the information we blame ourselves for the faulty recall. The reality is that our mind is not the fool‐proof safe we imagine it to be, but we can help it along when it comes to improving the retention of newly acquired knowledge or skills.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Learning happens through different methods. We have instant, powerful emotional learning experiences David Sousa<sup>1</sup>refers to as &ldquo;flashbulb memories,&rdquo; which cause instantaneous and long‐lasting memories of an event. This information is permanently retained in memory without any effort or choice.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>On the other end of the spectrum is information that is presented during learning related activities. These memories suffer a natural decline in retention. In 1885 Hermann Ebbinghous discovered the exponential nature of forgetting. Through repeated tests over various time periods he studied the memorization of nonsense syllables and defined the Ebbinghous Forgetting Curve<sup>2</sup>. What he found was that memory retention was relative to the strength of the memory and time.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h5>Applied to Modern Day Learning and Development</h5>\r\n<p>"Relative to the strength of the memory". What Ebbinghous discovered is that material will stick longer in memory if it is made more relevant and meaningful to the participant. This component is especially important as we want to ensure that all curricula are not only relevant but presented in a meaningful way. This encourages participants to relate to the material and makes it easier to grasp.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>"Time" &ndash; This factor is presented by Ebbinghouse as a multiplier. His learning curve initially demonstrates that the more time elapses the more material an individual forgets. His follow‐up experiments demonstrate that if you can practice learned skills/recite material at sufficient intervals then you can increase your retention.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The key to any successful training session is information retention. The key to retention is ensuring that the material participants are learning is relevant to them and that the curriculum is presented in a way that is also relevant and engaging.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Finally, we must also follow up all training with reinforcement activities and material on a regular basis to reinforce what participants have learned. Oftentimes, once training is delivered it is considered finished. Achieving return on a training investment means making sure participants are recalling, reusing and remembering what they have studied.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Even our memories need to be worked out every now and then to guarantee they are working at top form. For a solid training program, make certain that your participants get the most out of any training and ensure they are practicing their newly learned skills!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>(1)Sousa, David A. (2006). How the Brain Learns. Third Edition. Thousand Oaks, California. Corwin Press.</p>\r\n<p>(2) Memory: A Contribution to Experimental Psychology ‐‐ Ebbinghaus (1885/1913)</p>\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company &ndash;&ndash; 773‐572‐8616 &ndash; Chicago &ndash; Los Angeles &ndash; Sarasota &ndash; New York &ndash; India &ndash; Europe &ndash; Middle East &ndash; Asia</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>', '1', 'en'),
(61, '2016-12-19 09:32:36', '2016-12-19 10:09:48', 1, 'events-tab', '5 Simple Ways To Improve Virtual Meetings', 'Red Carpet Archives', '<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" align="center">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" valign="top" width="100%">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="middle" valign="bottom"><a href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?et=1103213581098&amp;s=3&amp;e=001FUVtYEibWy7mFnhMNuL64EDJXGDatASKse1uA07HrD4mwFF3nIIWGv1F61tOE_qzOY_oddEB7wxiH_ZS5eM7n3m_b3SfwFtsLLDQCxRAPCc=" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" shape="rect"><img class="img-responsive" src="http://ih.constantcontact.com/fs016/1101971666321/img/37.jpg" alt="The Red Carpet -   Pinnacle Performance Company Newsletter" width="600" height="200" name="ACCOUNT.IMAGE.37" border="0" /></a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" bgcolor="#1f4858">\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="2" rowspan="1" align="left" bgcolor="#ffffff" width="100%">\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" bgcolor="#cc0000">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" width="50%"><strong>Pinnacle Performance Company Newsletter</strong></td>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="right" width="50%">| Volume 2 | Issue 2</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" valign="top" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" valign="top">\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" bgcolor="#c7b87d">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n<p><img src="http://ih.constantcontact.com/fs016/1101971666321/img/40.jpg" alt="Center Stage" width="54" height="54" name="ACCOUNT.IMAGE.40" align="left" border="0" />5 Simple Ways to Improve <br /> Virtual Meetings</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\nIn the 1950\'s, theorist Wil Schutz1 conducted a groundbreaking study that identified three basic needs that individuals have in a collaborative environment (i.e. work or meeting environments): Inclusion, Control and Openness.<br /> <br /> The inability for some managers to transfer their management skills to the virtual environment has become a major stumbling block. Managers and team members that appeared effective previously may have overcome some of their shortcomings by virtue of the fact that they communicated together face-to-face.<br /> <br /> Incorporating the virtual meeting into the process of collaborating and production upsets the established mechanisms for the team to meet its basic needs as identified by Shutz.<br /> <br /> Taking away face-to-face interaction removes the automatic feeling of inclusion. It becomes easy to overlook individuals that are not in the same room with you, including their potential input and position on issues raised. As a meeting leader, it is critical to ensure that you are constantly polling for understanding and feedback from all parties. Additionally, the use of names will further strengthen all participants\' feelings of inclusion and connectedness.<br /> <br /> Control is an issue that everyone struggles with, whether conscious or subconscious. Moving to the virtual environment, individuals lose some of the tools available to help them control their environment. For instance, one<br /> can no longer indicate a desire to contribute by raising a hand or making gestures. A participant can no longer provide cues to indicate consensus or disapproval. The lack of these tools chips away at our ability to control the environment and the flow of conversation. Incorporating deliberate meeting processes and organization (i.e. a clearly communicated agenda), along with proper control mechanisms, will help attendees feel more in control of their own environment.\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<div><a href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?et=1103213581098&amp;s=3&amp;e=001FUVtYEibWy53ANEZUMiCpeKBHgqPRRBsuNN5yEeQQiObJx77VITDfRU-TAA8h-SBolcMh5a9X07aQ6ahktmVaix4RUzKS05t3G1znH_GEbu0zMkKiCsXQUyaZQ_93JXQ0_pZtbmlpUnb4PPc1Fr07vf-0L311EE_MyslfaRVOW8=" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" shape="rect">Click here to continue reading</a></div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="5" bgcolor="#ffffff">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" valign="top">\r\n<div><img src="http://ih.constantcontact.com/fs016/1101971666321/img/41.jpg" alt="Back Stage Pass" width="54" height="54" name="ACCOUNT.IMAGE.41" align="left" border="0" />Communication for the Virtual Environment - Get 50% off <br /> <br /> Ensure your message is received <br /> when you can\'t be seen</div>\r\n<br /> With today\'s global business demands, virtual meetings are a necessary alternative to their face-to-face counterparts. Lower costs, larger audiences, broader opportunities, immediacy and the ability to communicate more often make virtual communication a compelling and necessary choice. However, there are downsides to this new mode of communication: the absence of feedback, lack of eye contact and a reduced ability to control the focus of attendees, just to name a few. Virtual communicators must<br /> better prepare to overcome the challenges inherent in this evolving medium.<br /> <br /> 50% Off our Performance Based Communication <br /> for the Virtual Environment Curriculum<br /> <br /> Contact your Pinnacle representative and book a Performance Based Communication for the Virtual Environment workshop at your location before June 30th, 2010 and receive a 50% discount.<br /> <br /> For more information email us at <a href="mailto:info@pinper.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">info@pinper.com</a> or contact your local representative.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#9eafaa">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" height="1">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" bgcolor="#fdf2d6">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" width="99%">\r\n<p><img src="http://ih.constantcontact.com/fs016/1101971666321/img/42.jpg" alt="Back Stage   Pass" width="54" height="54" name="ACCOUNT.IMAGE.42" align="left" border="0" />Online Meeting Resources Recommendations from Pinnacle</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\nMany companies provide resources for enhancing virtual meetings. However, when looking for that tool to collaborate with meeting attendees or to share the visual portion of a message we\'ve put together a short list of virtual meeting resources:<br /> <br /> Webex - <a href="http://www.webex.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">http://www.webex.com/</a> - is a leading provider of on-line meeting and collaboration services. Since Webex does not require downloading of large files of software it easy to access for those who travel often. Pricing options range from 33-cents per minute, to a fixed monthly fee per user (roughly $75 per person per month for unlimited access packages).<br /> <br /> Fuze Meeting - <a href="http://www.fuzemeeting.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">http://www.fuzemeeting.com/</a> - has been designed for the more tech/social networking savvy users. It easily imports from Facebook, Twitter, Google Talk, Windows Live, Yahoo and Linked-In. In addition, it allows users to pay as you go by the minute or the month. Monthly plans starting at $29. <br /> <br /> GotoMeeting - <a href="http://www.gotomeeting.com/fec/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">http://www.gotomeeting.com/fec/</a> - has become the go to resource for on-line and on-demand collaboration services. It is easy to register as a user and host meetings immediately without the need for training. GotoMeeting does require that you install software on your computer. In addition to ease of use, its low cost, either a monthly subscription fee of $49/month or $468/year, makes this resource the #1 choice for experts in the field. <br /> <br /> Adobe also has a few options: <br /> ConnectNow - <a href="http://www.adobe.com/acom/connectnow/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">http://www.adobe.com/acom/connectnow/</a> - is a free and extremely simple web conferencing site that operates in your browser. Adobe designed it to be basic and painfully simple. It succeeds excellently! <br /> <br /> ConnectPro - <a href="http://www.adobe.com/products/acrobatconnectpro/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">http://www.adobe.com/products/acrobatconnectpro/</a> - If you are looking for a more complete Web Conferencing solution, Adobe\'s ConnectPro version has combined its multimedia features to allow businesses and individuals the ability to present, demonstrate, teach, train and collaborate in a secure, real-time virtual environment.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" bgcolor="#9eafaa">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" height="1">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" valign="top" width="100%">\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left">\r\n<p>Pinnacle Performance Company Contacts:</p>\r\n<p>Corporate Office: 773-572-8616 <br /> <br /> <u>USA</u><br /> South: 214-281-8625 <br /> Midwest: 773-572-8616 <br /> Northeast: 646-290-6711 <br /> Southeast: 941-870-2030 <br /> Southwest: 213-291-0660 <a href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?et=1103213581098&amp;s=3&amp;e=001FUVtYEibWy75PHLFeNGVQGhXUQVGI2K0bnjaSqaT_sqa-aDVh5Nt3UIeM8N7_8vc3H3N3L_7yTSyDzNMccV-vQ34A8--v3UufDmYqTuZukbAz7FQ6vIwIr9LlcOW1OOuo2P_5FeQzMFWubZXE7ZW3p7CN3jDWMCwAJFD5Gll4ZKYSkCTUCgDlA==" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" shape="rect"><img src="http://ih.constantcontact.com/fs016/1101971666321/img/34.jpg" alt="Back Stage Pass" width="108" height="73" name="ACCOUNT.IMAGE.34" align="right" border="0" /></a><br /> Northwest: 303-459-4291 <br /> <br /> <u>Asia Pacific</u><br /> Pune, India: +91 99700 01013</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" valign="top" bgcolor="#cc0000" width="150">\r\n<table border="0" width="150" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="left" valign="top" width="100%">\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center" valign="top"><strong>In This Issue</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="center"><a href="https://mail.google.com/mail/?ui=2&amp;view=bsp&amp;ver=ohhl4rw8mbn4https://mail.google.com/mail/?ui=2&amp;view=bsp&amp;ver=ohhl4rw8mbn4#12897b4c1837b0d4_LETTER.BLOCK4" rel="nofollow" shape="rect">Top Ten Movies of 2009</a></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" bgcolor="#cc0000">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="middle"><strong>Quick Links</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="middle">\r\n<div><a href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?et=1103213581098&amp;s=3&amp;e=001FUVtYEibWy7ZWw3ucN4VOSa55IXq6eiM-IAidSEbDvq2d3hyrUCsLN0GtTYxMPtr4YOvVmCP_SUwJMtDc4ddVjR12500_hSH_msWNLO6gfxyZWt1sqOLVZysvgVc70j2ua_obfejapICYVPnjGJohcv03c0Aj--vRrfQRZZFC8XE93RjYY0UP33bSDCjtSsakOL7fb3tcAgcCNnpImMwYQ==" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" shape="rect">Pinnacle News</a></div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><a href="http://site.pinnaclene.com/index.php?option=com_content&amp;task=blogcategory&amp;id=14&amp;Itemid=33" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" shape="rect">About Pinnacle</a></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" bgcolor="#cc0000">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="middle">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="middle"><strong>Upcoming Events </strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td colspan="1" rowspan="1" align="middle">\r\n<div>ASTD 2010</div>\r\n<strong>American Society for Training &amp; Development <br /> </strong>Chicago, IL\r\n<div>May 16 - May 19<br /> <strong><br /> </strong>SHRM 2010</div>\r\n<div>\r\n<div><strong>Society for Human Resource Management</strong><br /> San Diego, CA</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>June 27 - June 30</div>\r\n<div><br /> <img src="http://ih.constantcontact.com/fs016/1101971666321/img/43.jpg" alt="Back Stage Pass" width="54" height="54" name="ACCOUNT.IMAGE.43" border="0" /><br /> Pinnacle Workshops <br /> <br />\r\n<div>\r\n<div><strong>Pilot Workshops<br /> </strong></div>\r\n</div>\r\n<strong><br /> New York - May 6<br /> Chicago - May 26<br /> Atlanta - June 2<br /> Charlotte - June 3<br /> Detroit - June 8<br /> Cleveland - June 9<br /> Pittsburgh - June 10<br /> Dallas - June 15<br /> Houston - June 16<br /> <br /> Association Workshops<br /> <br /> <strong>ASTD Mid-Michigan<br /> April 20<br /> <br /> ASTD Silicon Valley <br /> May 11<br /> <br /> ASTD North East Wisconsin<br /> May 11<br /> <br /> Imperial Valley Human Resources Association - at the (IVHRA, an SHRM affiliate)<br /> August 11 </strong><br /> </strong>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n<